{"title_page": "Latvian National Symphony Orchestra", "text_new": "{{short description|Latvian symphony orchestra}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{use list-defined references|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox orchestra\n| name                = Latvian National Symphony Orchestra\n| type                = \n| native_name         = {{nobreak|Latvijas Nacion\u0101lais simfoniskais or\u0137estris}}\n| native_name_lang    = lv\n| short_name          = \n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| alt                 = \n| former_name         = {{ubl|Latvian Radio Centre Orchestra|Latvian RSO}}\n| founded             = {{Start date|1926}}\n| disbanded           = \n| later_name          = \n| location            = [[Riga]], Latvia\n| concert_hall        = [[Large Guild, Riga|Great Guild Hall]], [[Riga]]\n| principal_conductor = [[Andris Poga]]\n| music_director      = \n| website             = {{url|lnso.lv}}\n}}\nThe '''Latvian National Symphony Orchestra''' (LNSO), {{lang-lv|'''Latvijas Nacion\u0101lais simfoniskais or\u0137estris'''|italic=no}}, is the principal [[symphony orchestra]] of [[Latvia]]. It was founded in 1926 as the '''Latvian Radio Centre Orchestra''' by the conductor [[Arv\u012bds P\u0101rups]], and was the first permanent orchestra in the country.{{r|grove}}  \n\nLNSO's mission is to offer the Latvian public musical performances of the whole orchestral repertoire from the classics to contemporary compositions and to introduce audiences abroad with [[Latvian Music|Latvian music]]. One of the LNSO's most important priorities is to attract young listeners with educational programmes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.lnso.lv/par-lnso|title=PAR LNSO|website=LNSO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe LNSO is a six-time winner of the [http://www.muzikasbalva.lv/ Latvian Grand Music Award] (1993, 2009, 2012, 2013, 2016 and 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.muzikasbalva.lv/laureati|title=Liel\u0101 m\u016bzikas balva - Laure\u0101ti|website=www.muzikasbalva.lv|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nSince 2013 the music director of the LNSO is maestro [[Andris Poga]]. Beginning with the 2021/2022 season Poga will take up the position of chief conductor of the [[Stavanger Symphony Orchestra]] in [[Norway|Norway.]] \n\nThe orchestra\u2019s most notable former music directors are [[J\u0101nis Medi\u0146\u0161]], [[Leon\u012bds V\u012bgners]], [[Edgars Tons]], [[Vassily Sinaisky]] (the LNSO\u2019s honorary guest conductor since 2017), [[Olari Elts]], and [[Karel Mark Chichon]]. The LNSO\u2019s guest conductors include Latvians [[Arv\u012bds Jansons]], [[Mariss Jansons]] and [[Andris Nelsons]], as well as [[Valery Gergiev]], [[Neeme J\u00e4rvi]], [[Paavo J\u00e4rvi]], [[Kirill Kondrashin]], [[Kurt Masur]], [[Krzysztof Penderecki]], [[Gennady Rozhdestvensky]], [[Yevgeny Svetlanov]], [[Yuri Simonov]], and many others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.lnso.lv/par-lnso|title=PAR LNSO|website=LNSO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years the LNSO has performed at the [[Philharmonie de Paris]] and the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs Elys\u00e9es]], the [[Alte Oper]] [[Frankfurt]] and the Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre of [[Aix-en-Provence]] among many other European [[concert halls]]. The orchestra has participated in music festivals in [[France]], [[Germany]] and [[Switzerland]] as well as the [[Bratislava Music Festival]]. On its most recent tours the LNSO teamed up with Latvian violinist [[Baiba Skride]], cellist [[Alexander Kniazev|Alexander Knyazev]], pianists [[Nicholas Angelich]] and [[Boris Berezovsky (pianist)|Boris Berezovsky]], and the rising stars [[Lukas Geniu\u0161as]] and [[Lucas Debargue]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.lnso.lv/par-lnso|title=PAR LNSO|website=LNSO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to regular symphonic concerts, the orchestra also broadcasts and records. Its primary performance venue is the [[Large Guild, Riga|Great Guild Hall]] in [[Riga]].{{r|szu|page=307}}\n\n== Music Directors and Chief Conductors ==\n\n* [[Andris Poga]] (Since November 2013 \u2013 present)\n* [[Karel Mark Chichon]] (2009\u201312)\n* [[Olari Elts]] (2001\u20132005)\n* [[Terje Mikkelsen]] (1997\u20132001)\n* [[Paul M\u00e4gi]] (1990\u20131994)\n* [[Vassily Sinaisky]] (1975\u20131987)\n* [[Leon\u012bds V\u012bgners]] (1949\u20131963, 1966\u20131974)\n* [[Edgars Tons]] (1963\u20131966)\n* [[Dmitrijs Ku\u013ckovs]] (1945\u20131949)\n* [[J\u0101nis Medi\u0146\u0161]] (1928\u20131944)\n* [[Arv\u012bds P\u0101rups]] (1926\u20131928)\n\n==Selected recordings==\n* [[Inessa Galante]] Debut recital Latvian National Symphony Orchestra Conducted by [[Alexander Vilumanis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=grove>Joachim Braun, Arnolds Kloti\u0146\u0161, Martin Boiko (2001). [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000042158 Latvia]. ''Grove Music Online''. {{subscription required}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=szu>Szu Ping Chan (editor) (2009). [https://books.google.it/books?id=eP30EnnP_5UC&pg=PA307 ''Anthem Guide to the Opera, Concert Halls and Classical Music Venues of Europe'']. London; New York: Anthem Press. {{isbn|9781843312727}}.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Classical music in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Latvian orchestras]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1926]]\n[[Category:National orchestras]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations established in 1926]]\n\n\n{{Orchestra-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Latvian symphony orchestra}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{use list-defined references|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox orchestra\n| name                = Latvian National Symphony Orchestra\n| type                = \n| native_name         = {{nobreak|Latvijas Nacion\u0101lais simfoniskais or\u0137estris}}\n| native_name_lang    = lv\n| short_name          = \n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| alt                 = \n| former_name         = {{ubl|Latvian Radio Centre Orchestra|Latvian RSO}}\n| founded             = {{Start date|1926}}\n| disbanded           = \n| later_name          = \n| location            = [[Riga]], Latvia\n| concert_hall        = [[Large Guild, Riga|Great Guild Hall]], [[Riga]]\n| principal_conductor = [[Andris Poga]]\n| music_director      = \n| website             = {{url|lnso.lv}}\n}}\nThe '''Latvian National Symphony Orchestra''' (LNSO), {{lang-lv|'''Latvijas Nacion\u0101lais simfoniskais or\u0137estris'''|italic=no}}, is the principal [[symphony orchestra]] of [[Latvia]]. It was founded in 1926 as the '''Latvian Radio Centre Orchestra''' by the conductor [[Arv\u012bds P\u0101rups]], and was the first permanent orchestra in the country.{{r|grove}}  \n\nLNSO's mission is to offer the Latvian public musical performances of the whole orchestral repertoire from the classics to contemporary compositions and to introduce audiences abroad with [[Latvian Music|Latvian music]]. One of the LNSO's most important priorities is to attract young listeners with educational programmes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.lnso.lv/par-lnso|title=PAR LNSO|website=LNSO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nThe LNSO is a six-time winner of the [http://www.muzikasbalva.lv/ Latvian Grand Music Award] (1993, 2009, 2012, 2013, 2016 and 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.muzikasbalva.lv/laureati|title=Liel\u0101 m\u016bzikas balva - Laure\u0101ti|website=www.muzikasbalva.lv|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nSince 2013 the music director of the LNSO is maestro [[Andris Poga]]. Beginning with the 2021/2022 season Poga will take up the position of chief conductor of the [[Stavanger Symphony Orchestra]] in [[Norway|Norway.]] \n\nThe orchestra\u2019s most notable former music directors are [[J\u0101nis Medi\u0146\u0161]], [[Leon\u012bds V\u012bgners]], [[Edgars Tons]], [[Vassily Sinaisky]] (the LNSO\u2019s honorary guest conductor since 2017), [[Olari Elts]], and [[Karel Mark Chichon]]. The LNSO\u2019s guest conductors include Latvians [[Arv\u012bds Jansons]], [[Mariss Jansons]] and [[Andris Nelsons]], as well as [[Valery Gergiev]], [[Neeme J\u00e4rvi]], [[Paavo J\u00e4rvi]], [[Kirill Kondrashin]], [[Kurt Masur]], [[Krzysztof Penderecki]], [[Gennady Rozhdestvensky]], [[Yevgeny Svetlanov]], [[Yuri Simonov]], and many others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.lnso.lv/par-lnso|title=PAR LNSO|website=LNSO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years the LNSO has performed at the [[Philharmonie de Paris]] and the [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es|Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs Elys\u00e9es]], the [[Alte Oper]] [[Frankfurt]] and the Grand Th\u00e9\u00e2tre of [[Aix-en-Provence]] among many other European [[concert halls]]. The orchestra has participated in music festivals in [[France]], [[Germany]] and [[Switzerland]] as well as the [[Bratislava Music Festival]]. On its most recent tours the LNSO teamed up with Latvian violinist [[Baiba Skride]], cellist [[Alexander Kniazev|Alexander Knyazev]], pianists [[Nicholas Angelich]] and [[Boris Berezovsky (pianist)|Boris Berezovsky]], and the rising stars [[Lukas Geniu\u0161as]] and [[Lucas Debargue]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.lnso.lv/par-lnso|title=PAR LNSO|website=LNSO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to regular symphonic concerts, the orchestra also broadcasts and records. Its primary performance venue is the [[Large Guild, Riga|Great Guild Hall]] in [[Riga]].{{r|szu|page=307}}\n\n==Conductors==\n*Chief Conductor and Artistic Director\n** [[Paul M\u00e4gi]] (1990\u20131994)\n**[[Andris Poga]] (Since November 2013 \u2013 present)\n*Conductors\n**[[Karel Mark Chichon]] (2009\u201312)\n**[[Dmitry Yablonsky]]\n**Guillermo Garci'a Calvo\n**[[Hartmut Haenchen]]\n**Ge'rard Korsten\n**Rossen Milanov\n**[[Andris Nelsons]]\n**[[Tomomi Nishimoto]]\n**Modestas Pitrenas\n**Ola Rudner\n**[[Yuri Simonov]]\n**Andris Vecumnieks\n\n==Selected recordings==\n* [[Inessa Galante]] Debut recital Latvian National Symphony Orchestra Conducted by [[Alexander Vilumanis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=grove>Joachim Braun, Arnolds Kloti\u0146\u0161, Martin Boiko (2001). [http://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000042158 Latvia]. ''Grove Music Online''. {{subscription required}}.</ref>\n\n<ref name=szu>Szu Ping Chan (editor) (2009). [https://books.google.it/books?id=eP30EnnP_5UC&pg=PA307 ''Anthem Guide to the Opera, Concert Halls and Classical Music Venues of Europe'']. London; New York: Anthem Press. {{isbn|9781843312727}}.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Classical music in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Latvian orchestras]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1926]]\n[[Category:National orchestras]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations established in 1926]]\n\n\n{{Orchestra-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Evelynjuniper", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed the list of music directors and chief conductors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latvian_National_Symphony_Orchestra"}
{"title_page": "Shan-chwen Chang", "text_new": "{{Userspace draft|source=ArticleWizard|date=April 2020}} \n\n'''Shan-chwen Chang''' ({{zh|c=\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3}}) is Vice President of [[National Taiwan University]] and convenes the advisory specialist panel of the {{ill|Central Epidemic Command Center|zh|\u4e2d\u592e\u6d41\u884c\u75ab\u60c5\u6307\u63ee\u4e2d\u5fc3}} (CECC) in Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3915306|title=CECC expert breaks down coronavirus symptoms ...|last=News|first=Taiwan|website=Taiwan News|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He is Professor of Medicine in the University's Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ntuvp.ntu.edu.tw/English/vpformed.html|title=Welcome to NTU Executive Vice President Office|website=ntuvp.ntu.edu.tw|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n== COVID-19 pandemic in Taiwan ==\nProfessor Chang is attending regular press conferences to provide the public with updates about the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/life/breakingnews/3113521|title=\u9019\u75c5\u6bd2\u4e0d\u5c0b\u5e38\uff01\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u9ad4\u5167\u6709\u6297\u9ad4\u3001\u547c\u5438\u9053\u4ecd\u6709\u75c5\u6bd2 - \u751f\u6d3b - \u81ea\u7531\u6642\u5831\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|date=2020-03-26|website=\u81ea\u7531\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He says that of the current confirmed cases in Taiwan, the symptoms are mainly fever, respiratory symptoms, and loss of olfactory taste.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.storm.mg/article/2519444|title=\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u78ba\u8a3a\u8005\u51fa\u73fe\u808c\u8089\u75e0\u75db \u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u4e0d\u5e38\u898b\uff0c\u66ab\u4e0d\u5217\u5165\u901a\u5831-\u98a8\u50b3\u5a92|last=Storm.mg|date=2020-04-14|website=www.storm.mg|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nHe notes that the two groups most susceptible to coronavirus are students and members of tour groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20200331006070-260405?chdtv|title=\u54ea\u8077\u696d\u6613\u67d3\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\uff1f\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u90192\u65cf\u7fa4\u6700\u591a - \u751f\u6d3b|last=\u4e2d\u6642\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|website=\u4e2d\u6642\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He has also said there has been an increasing numbers of confirmed COVID-19 infected patients with diarrhoea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202004050014|title=Further self-health management needed after home quarantine: CECC - Focus Taiwan|website=focustaiwan.tw|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He has noted that the CECC decided to expand screening to patients with pneumonia \u2013 hoping to detect those infected with COVID-19 more quickly and before they infect others.<ref>[https://www.ocac.gov.tw/OCAC/Eng/Pages/Detail.aspx?nodeid=329&pid=15949154 OCAC.R.O.C.(Taiwan) \u2013 News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In March 2020, Professor Chang helped to investigate one particularly mysterious domestic case of COVID-19.<ref>[https://news.immigration.gov.tw/PH/NewsTopic.aspx?NEWSGUID=adafe537-a819-49de-913e-1ac2ab878615 Global News for New immigrants-Taiwan experts trying to solve mystery of domestic coronavirus case<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nProfessor Chang has responded to questions about links between smoking and susceptibility to symptoms of the coronavirus, saying it is too early to draw conclusions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.udn.com/health/story/120951/4488841|title=\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\u89e3\u6790\u53f0\u7063\u65b0\u51a0\u75c5\u4f8b \u6709\u9019\u500b\u7fd2\u6163\u7684\u4eba\u75c5\u60c5\u6bd4\u8f03\u56b4\u91cd {{!}} \u5c08\u5bb6\u89c0\u9ede {{!}} \u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e|website=\u5143\u6c23\u7db2|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He has also pointed out that his colleagues have been communicating with [[The World Health Organization]] (WHO), which is taking a great interest in how Taiwan is dealing so effectively with the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tw.news.yahoo.com/%E5%BF%AB%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E-%E5%8F%B0%E7%81%A3%E6%98%A8%E6%97%A5%E8%88%87%E4%B8%96%E8%A1%9B%E9%80%9A%E9%9B%BB%E8%A9%B1-%E5%BC%B5%E4%B8%8A%E6%B7%B3-%E5%8F%B0%E7%81%A3%E4%BB%8D%E4%B8%8D%E5%9C%A8%E7%96%AB%E8%8B%97%E7%A0%94%E7%99%BC%E6%9C%83%E8%AD%B0%E5%B0%8F%E7%B5%84%E8%A3%A1-065741887.html|title=\u5feb\u65b0\u805e\uff0f\u53f0\u7063\u6628\u65e5\u8207\u4e16\u885b\u901a\u96fb\u8a71\uff01 \u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u53f0\u7063\u4ecd\u4e0d\u5728\u75ab\u82d7\u7814\u767c\u6703\u8b70\u5c0f\u7d44\u88e1|website=tw.news.yahoo.com|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Academic background ==\nProfessor Chang has previously held posts including Chief, Division of Infection, Immunology and Rheumatology, Department of Internal Medicine, at [[National Taiwan University Hospital]]; and Dean, National Taiwan University College of Medicine. \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\nProfessor Shan-chwen Chang's [http://ntuvp.ntu.edu.tw/English/vpformed.html Faculty Page] at National Taiwan University.\n\n[[Category:Taiwanese medical researchers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese academics]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Userspace draft|source=ArticleWizard|date=April 2020}} \n\n'''Shan-chwen Chang''' ({{zh|c=\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3}}) is Vice President of [[National Taiwan University]] and convenes the advisory specialist panel of the {{ill|Central Epidemic Command Center|zh|\u4e2d\u592e\u6d41\u884c\u75ab\u60c5\u6307\u63ee\u4e2d\u5fc3}} (CECC) in Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3915306|title=CECC expert breaks down coronavirus symptoms ...|last=News|first=Taiwan|website=Taiwan News|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He is Professor of Medicine in the University's Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ntuvp.ntu.edu.tw/English/vpformed.html|title=Welcome to NTU Executive Vice President Office|website=ntuvp.ntu.edu.tw|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n== COVID-19 pandemic in Taiwan ==\nProfessor Chang is attending regular press conferences to provide the public with updates about the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/life/breakingnews/3113521|title=\u9019\u75c5\u6bd2\u4e0d\u5c0b\u5e38\uff01\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u9ad4\u5167\u6709\u6297\u9ad4\u3001\u547c\u5438\u9053\u4ecd\u6709\u75c5\u6bd2 - \u751f\u6d3b - \u81ea\u7531\u6642\u5831\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|date=2020-03-26|website=\u81ea\u7531\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> he says that of the current confirmed cases in Taiwan, the symptoms are mainly fever, respiratory symptoms, and loss of olfactory taste.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.storm.mg/article/2519444|title=\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u78ba\u8a3a\u8005\u51fa\u73fe\u808c\u8089\u75e0\u75db \u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u4e0d\u5e38\u898b\uff0c\u66ab\u4e0d\u5217\u5165\u901a\u5831-\u98a8\u50b3\u5a92|last=Storm.mg|date=2020-04-14|website=www.storm.mg|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\nHe notes that the two groups most susceptible to coronavirus are students and members of tour groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinatimes.com/realtimenews/20200331006070-260405?chdtv|title=\u54ea\u8077\u696d\u6613\u67d3\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\uff1f\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u90192\u65cf\u7fa4\u6700\u591a - \u751f\u6d3b|last=\u4e2d\u6642\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|website=\u4e2d\u6642\u96fb\u5b50\u5831|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He has also said there has been an increasing numbers of confirmed COVID-19 infected patients with diarrhoea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://focustaiwan.tw/society/202004050014|title=Further self-health management needed after home quarantine: CECC - Focus Taiwan|website=focustaiwan.tw|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He has noted that the CECC decided to expand screening to patients with pneumonia \u2013 hoping to detect those infected with COVID-19 more quickly and before they infect others.<ref>[https://www.ocac.gov.tw/OCAC/Eng/Pages/Detail.aspx?nodeid=329&pid=15949154 OCAC.R.O.C.(Taiwan) \u2013 News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In March 2020, Professor Chang helped to investigate one particularly mysterious domestic case of COVID-19.<ref>[https://news.immigration.gov.tw/PH/NewsTopic.aspx?NEWSGUID=adafe537-a819-49de-913e-1ac2ab878615 Global News for New immigrants-Taiwan experts trying to solve mystery of domestic coronavirus case<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nProfessor Chang has responded to questions about links between smoking and susceptibility to symptoms of the coronavirus, saying it is too early to draw conclusions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.udn.com/health/story/120951/4488841|title=\u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\u89e3\u6790\u53f0\u7063\u65b0\u51a0\u75c5\u4f8b \u6709\u9019\u500b\u7fd2\u6163\u7684\u4eba\u75c5\u60c5\u6bd4\u8f03\u56b4\u91cd {{!}} \u5c08\u5bb6\u89c0\u9ede {{!}} \u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e|website=\u5143\u6c23\u7db2|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He has also pointed out that his colleagues have been communicating with [[The World Health Organization]] (WHO), which is taking a great interest in how Taiwan is dealing so effectively with the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tw.news.yahoo.com/%E5%BF%AB%E6%96%B0%E8%81%9E-%E5%8F%B0%E7%81%A3%E6%98%A8%E6%97%A5%E8%88%87%E4%B8%96%E8%A1%9B%E9%80%9A%E9%9B%BB%E8%A9%B1-%E5%BC%B5%E4%B8%8A%E6%B7%B3-%E5%8F%B0%E7%81%A3%E4%BB%8D%E4%B8%8D%E5%9C%A8%E7%96%AB%E8%8B%97%E7%A0%94%E7%99%BC%E6%9C%83%E8%AD%B0%E5%B0%8F%E7%B5%84%E8%A3%A1-065741887.html|title=\u5feb\u65b0\u805e\uff0f\u53f0\u7063\u6628\u65e5\u8207\u4e16\u885b\u901a\u96fb\u8a71\uff01 \u5f35\u4e0a\u6df3\uff1a\u53f0\u7063\u4ecd\u4e0d\u5728\u75ab\u82d7\u7814\u767c\u6703\u8b70\u5c0f\u7d44\u88e1|website=tw.news.yahoo.com|language=zh-Hant-TW|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Academic background ==\nProfessor Chang has previously held posts including Chief, Division of Infection, Immunology and Rheumatology, Department of Internal Medicine, at [[National Taiwan University Hospital]]; and Dean, National Taiwan University College of Medicine. \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\nProfessor Shan-chwen Chang's [http://ntuvp.ntu.edu.tw/English/vpformed.html Faculty Page] at National Taiwan University.\n\n[[Category:Taiwanese medical researchers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese academics]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Taiwan]]\n", "name_user": "MerlinVtwelve", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCOVID-19 pandemic in Taiwan:Typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shan-chwen_Chang"}
{"title_page": "One Thousand Museum", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = \u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0647\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u0648\u0632\u0647\n| status = \u0627\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a\n| image = One Thousand Museum March 2019.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \u0645\u0627\u0631\u0633 \u06f2\u06f0\u06f1\u06f9\n| location = \u0627\u06cc\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a \u0645\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0647 \u060c \u0641\u0644\u0648\u0631\u06cc\u062f\u0627 \u060c \u0645\u06cc\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u060c \u0628\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0631 \u0628\u06cc\u0633\u06a9\u06cc\u0646\u060c \u0634\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06f1\u06f0\u06f0\u06f0\n| coordinates = {{coord|25.7841|-80.1900|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-FL|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type = Florida\n| start_date = \u06f2\u06f0\u06f1\u06f5\n| completion_date = \n| destruction_date = \n| architect = \u0632\u0647\u0627 \u062d\u062f\u06cc\u062f\n| owner = \n| cost = \n| floor_area = \n| top_floor = \n| floor_count = \u0637\u0628\u0642\u0647 \u06f6\u06f2\n| references = \n| building_type = \u0645\u0633\u06a9\u0648\u0646\u06cc\n| antenna_spire = \n| roof = \u06f2\u06f1\u06f5 \u0645\u062a\u0631\n| elevator_count = \n| structural_engineer = \n| main_contractor = \u0634\u0631\u06a9\u062a \u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a \u0648 \u0633\u0627\u0632 \u067e\u0644\u0627\u0632\u0627\n| est_completion = \u0627\u0648\u0627\u062e\u0631 \u06f2\u06f0\u06f1\u06f8\n| opening = \n| demolished_date = \n| developer = \n| management = \n}}\n\n\"\u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0647\u0632\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u0648\u0632\u0647\" \u06cc\u06a9 \u0622\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062e\u0631\u0627\u0634 \u0645\u0633\u06a9\u0648\u0646\u06cc \u0648\u0627\u0642\u0639 \u062f\u0631 \u0634\u0647\u0631 \u0645\u06cc\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a . \u0627\u06cc\u0646 \u0628\u0646\u0627 \u062a\u0648\u0633\u0637\" \u0632\u0647\u0627 \u062d\u062f\u06cc\u062f \" \u0622\u0631\u0634\u06cc\u062a\u06a9\u062a \u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u06cc\u062a\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u06cc\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0646\u062f\u0647 \u062c\u0627\u06cc\u0632\u0647 \u0645\u0639\u0645\u0627\u0631\u06cc \u067e\u0631\u06cc\u062a\u0632\u06a9\u0631 \u0637\u0631\u0627\u062d\u06cc \u0634\u062f\u0647 \u0627\u0633\u062a . \u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0634\u0627\u0645\u0644 \u06f6\u06f2 \u0637\u0628\u0642\u0647 \u0648 \u0628\u0647 \u0627\u0631\u062a\u0641\u0627\u0639 \u06f2\u06f1\u06f5 \u0645\u062a\u0631 \u0645\u06cc\u0628\u0627\u0634\u062f \u06a9\u0647 \u06cc\u06a9\u06cc \u0627\u0632 \u0628\u0644\u0646\u062f\u062a\u0631\u06cc\u0646 \u0633\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646\u0647\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u06cc\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a.\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat|1000 Museum}}\n* {{official|http://1000museum.com/}}\n* [http://onethousandmiami.com/pdf/One-Thousand-Museum.pdf One Thousand Museum (PDF)]\n\n{{Future Miami skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in the United States]]\n[[Category:Zaha Hadid buildings]]\n{{Florida-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name                = One Thousand Museum\n| status              = Completed\n| image               = One Thousand Museum March 2019.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px\n| caption             = March 2019\n| location            = 1000 [[Biscayne Boulevard]], [[Miami]], [[Florida]], [[United States]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|25.7841|-80.1900|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-FL|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type            = Florida\n| start_date          = 2015\n| completion_date     =\n| destruction_date    =\n| architect           = Zaha Hadid Architects (architect_of_record = [http://www.odparchitects.com ODP Architects & Interior Design])\n| owner               =\n| cost                =\n| floor_area          = 950,000 GFA\n| top_floor           =\n| floor_count         = 62<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web |url = http://www.emporis.com/buildings/1211439/one-thousand-museum-miami-fl-usa |title = One Thousand Museum |publisher = [[Emporis]] |accessdate = March 6, 2017 }}</ref>\n| references          =\n| building_type       = Residential\n| antenna_spire       =\n| roof                = {{convert|707|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n| elevator_count      =\n| structural_engineer = DeSimone Consulting Engineers\n| main_contractor     = Plaza Construction\n| est_completion      = late 2018\n| opening             =\n| demolished_date     =\n| developer           = 1000 Biscayne Tower, LLC\n| management          =\n}}\n\n'''[[One Thousand Museum]]''' is a high-rise residential condominium under construction in [[Miami]], Florida, United States. The building, which is located at 1000 [[Biscayne Boulevard]], across from [[Museum Park (Miami)|Museum Park]], was designed by [[Pritzker Prize]]-winning architect [[Zaha Hadid]].<ref name=\"SSCenter\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscrapercenter.com/building/one-thousand-museum-tower/15188|title=One Thousand Museum Tower|publisher=[[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]]|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref> After the death of Hadid, the Project Director of [[Zaha Hadid Architects]], Chris Lepine, completed the project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mansionglobal.com/articles/zaha-hadid-architects-chris-lepine-says-luxury-is-about-being-carefree-and-pampered-104717|title=Zaha Hadid Architects\u2019 Chris Lepine Says Luxury is About Being \u2018Carefree and Pampered\u2019|last=Blatter|first=Lucy Cohen|access-date=2018-08-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Completed in 2019, the 62-story building stands at a height of {{convert|707|ft|m}}, making it one of the [[List of tallest buildings in Miami|tallest buildings in Miami]].<ref name=\"SSCenter\" />\n\nThe [[deep foundation]] required drilling to record depths of over {{convert|170|ft|m}} by HJ Foundation, part of the [[Keller Group]].<ref name=\"Heralddeep\">{{cite news|URL=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/business/article17333627.html |title = Contractors drill to record depths for downtown condo tower |work = [[The Miami Herald]] |date = April 3, 2015 |accessdate = April 3, 2015 }}</ref>  The depths of two auger-cast piles broke a record for [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]] that had recently been set by HJ Foundation at the [[Porsche Design Tower]] in [[Sunny Isles Beach]].<ref name=\"Heralddeep\" />  \n\nThe exotic design of the building features a curving exoskeleton partially obscuring the balconies<ref name=\"huffpost\">{{cite news |url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/18/zaha-hadid-miami_n_2900525.html? |title = Zaha Hadid's One Thousand Museum: A Futuristic Skyscraper In Downtown Miami |work = [[The Huffington Post]] |date = March 18, 2013 |accessdate = April 3, 2015 }}</ref> that also serves structural purposes, allowing the interior space to have fewer columns.<ref name=\"archmag\">{{cite web |url = http://www.architectmagazine.com/design/miamis-luxury-highrise-one-thousand-museum-tower-designed-by-zaha-hadid-architects_o |title = Miami's Luxury Highrise, One Thousand Museum Tower, Designed by Zaha Hadid Architects |work = [[Architecture (magazine)|Architecture]] |date = April 3, 2014 |accessdate = April 3, 2015 }}</ref> To meet the architect's designs of smoothness and finish, the columns were finished with [[glass fiber reinforced concrete]] permanent form works. The effect of the design and height on [[wind loading]] is part of the reason the foundation had to be exceptionally deep.<ref name=\"TNM\">{{cite web |url = http://www.thenextmiami.com/index.php/contractors-drill-record-breaking-depths-build-foundation-zaha-hadids-one-thousand-museum/ |title = Contractors Drill To Record-Breaking Depths To Build Foundation For Zaha Hadid\u2019s One Thousand Museum |publisher = The Next Miami |date = January 29, 2015 |accessdate = April 3, 2015 }}</ref> The building is considered ultra-luxury, containing about 84 large units priced at about double the cost per square foot of nearby condominium towers, with amenities possibly including a rooftop [[helipad]].<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/morganbrennan/2013/08/05/developers-create-limited-edition-residences-in-luxury-housings-latest-trend/ |title = Luxury Housing's Latest Trend: 'Limited-Edition' Residences |work = [[Forbes]] |date = August 5, 2013 |accessdate = April 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, before the building was finished, an episode of PBS' ''Impossible Builds'' featured the building, which they referred to as the \"scorpion tower\",<ref name=\"PBS\">{{cite web |url = http://www.pbs.org/video/the-scorpion-tower-jsrv5j/ |title = The Scorpion Tower |work = Impossible Builds |publisher = PBS |accessdate = February 18, 2018 }}</ref> and described it as \"one of the most complex skyscrapers ever to make it off the drawing board.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.archdaily.com/892505/drone-footage-shows-zaha-hadids-one-thousand-museum-tower-nearing-completion|title=Drone Footage Shows Zaha Hadid's One Thousand Museum Tower Nearing Completion|date=2018-08-08|website=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\nDesigned by Iraqi-British architect Zaha Hadid, One Thousand Museum was Zaha Hadid's first residential tower in the Western Hemisphere, and one the final projects designed by Hadid in her lifetime.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was designed in association with O\u2019Donnell Dannwolf Partners Architects, a local architecture firm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.archdaily.com/772754/zaha-hadids-one-thousand-museum-begins-construction-in-miami|title=Construction Begins on Zaha Hadid's One Thousand Museum in Miami|date=2015-09-01|website=ArchDaily|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> \n\nA notable feature of the building is the curving exoskeleton, allowing the interior space to have fewer columns. The exoskeleton is composed of 5,000 pieces of [[glass fiber reinforced concrete]].<ref name=\":0\" /> These pieces were shipped from [[Dubai]] early in the construction process. The exoskeleton is located in front of a glass facade.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dezeen.com/2018/02/15/one-thousand-museum-tower-amenity-spaces-zaha-hadid-tops-out-miami-florida/|title=Zaha Hadid's One Thousand Museum tower tops out in Miami|date=2018-02-15|website=Dezeen|language=en|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\nThe building was topped out in February 2018.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Facilities ==\nWhen completed, the building will contain 84 residences, consisting of a two-story duplex penthouse, 4 townhouses, 10 full-floor residences, and 70 half-floor units.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.archdaily.com/tag/one-thousand-museum|title=One Thousand Museum {{!}} Tag {{!}} ArchDaily|website=www.archdaily.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref> \n\nA swimming pool is installed at the top of the building, to be covered by a curving, faceted metal ceiling that will reflect the water. The double-height space is occupied by the pool on one side and a seating area on the other. A similar metallic canopy design will be used for the bar. A full two-room treatment spa, hair and beauty salon, acai and juice bar fueled by Raw Republic, and a sunbathing area is also installed, alongside a multimedia tower.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:1000 Museum construction December 2016.jpg|December 2016\nFile:One Thousand Museum August 2017.jpg|August 2017\nFile:One Thousand Museum construction December 2017.jpg|December 2017; exoskeleton is clearly shown.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat|1000 Museum}}\n* {{official|http://1000museum.com/}}\n* [http://onethousandmiami.com/pdf/One-Thousand-Museum.pdf One Thousand Museum (PDF)]\n\n{{Future Miami skyscrapers}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures under construction in the United States]]\n[[Category:Zaha Hadid buildings]]\n{{Florida-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Fargondm", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Translation to Persian)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One_Thousand_Museum"}
