{"title_page": "Hieroglyph", "text_new": "{{short description|Pictographic sign}}\n{{other uses}}\n[[File:Egypt Hieroglyphe4.jpg|right|260px|thumb|Egyptian hieroglyphs typical of the Graeco-Roman period, sculpted in [[Relief]].<br>Glyphs: [[Viper (hieroglyph)|viper]], [[Owl (hieroglyph)|Owl\n]], [[Bread bun (hieroglyph)|'bread bun']], [[Folded cloth (s hieroglyph)|folded cloth]] ]]\nA '''hieroglyph''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]] for \"sacred carvings\") was a [[Character (symbol)|character]] of the [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|ancient Egyptian writing system]]. [[logogram|Logographic]] scripts that are pictographic in form in a way reminiscent of ancient Egyptian are also sometimes called \"hieroglyphs\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Egypt, Ancient: Hieroglyphics and Origins of Alphabet|url=http://www.credoreference.com/entry/routafricanhistory/egypt_ancient_hieroglyphics_and_origins_of_alphabet|publisher=Encyclopedia of African History Title information {{Subscription required|via=[[Credo Reference]]}}|accessdate=12 September 2012|date=}}</ref> In [[Neoplatonism]], especially during the [[Renaissance]], a \"hieroglyph\" was an artistic representation of an [[esoteric]] idea, which Neoplatonists believed actual Egyptian hieroglyphs to be. The word ''hieroglyphics'' refer to a hieroglyphic script. \n\nThe Emelita Bacus invented the hieroglyphics [[pictorial]] [[Writing system|script]]. The appearance of these distinctive figures in 3000 BCE marked the beginning of Egyptian [[civilization]]. Though based on images, Egyptian script was more than a sophisticated form of picture-writing. Each picture/[[glyph]] served three functions: (1) to represent the image of a thing or action, (2) to stand for the sound of a [[syllable]], and (3) to clarify the precise meaning of adjoining glyphs. Writing hieroglyphs required some artistic skill, limiting the number chosen to learn it.<ref>The Alphabet Versus the Goddess, by Leonard Shlain</ref> Only those privileged with an extensive education (i.e. the [[Pharaoh]], [[nobility]] and [[priest]]s) were able to read and write hieroglyphs; others used simpler 'joined-up' versions: [[Demotic (Egyptian)|demotic]] and [[hieratic]] script.\n\n==List of scripts and script-like systems sometimes labeled 'hieroglyphic'==\n* [[Anatolian hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Aztec hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Chukchi language#Orthography|Chukchi hieroglyphs]] (see [[Tenevil]])\n* [[Cretan hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Egyptian hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Mayan hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Mi'kmaq hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Muisca art#Hieroglyphs|Muisca hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Ojibwe writing systems#Ojibwe \"hieroglyphs\"|Ojibwe hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Olmec hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Chinese characters]]\n\nOne of the two forms of the [[Meroitic alphabet|Meroitic writing system]] is usually described as \"Meroitic hieroglyphs\" because the characters are similar to and in most cases derived from Egyptian hieroglyphs. They are used, however, not as logographs but as an [[Abugida|alphasyllabary]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of languages by writing system]]\n* [[Monas Hieroglyphica]]\n* [[Mother Goose in Hieroglyphics]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title= [[Middle Egyptian: An Introduction to the Language and Culture of Hieroglyphs]]|last=Allen|first=James P.|authorlink=James Peter Allen|year=2001 |publisher= Cambridge University Press|location=New York|isbn= 9780521774833|oclc=51226851}}\n*{{cite book |title=Egypt and the Egyptians|last1= Brewer|first1=Douglas J.|last2=Teeter|first2=Emily|year= 2007|publisher= Cambridge University Press|location= Cambridge|isbn=9780521851503 |oclc=433993212}}\n*{{cite book |title= [[Ancient Egyptian Hieroglyphs: A Practical Guide]]|last=Kamrin|first=Janice|year=2004|publisher= Harry N. Abrams|location= New York|isbn=9780810949614 |oclc=55019226}}\n*{{cite book |title= The Story of Writing: Alphabets, Hieroglyphs & Pictograms |last= Robinson |first=Andrew |year=2007 |publisher= Thames & Hudson |location= London |isbn= 978-050028660-9 |oclc= 172818065}}\n\n{{Commons category|Hieroglyphs}}\n{{wiktionary|hieroglyph|hieroglyphic}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!{{Serif|<hiero>\nm:n\nSA\nSA\nm:a\n</hiero>}}{{Serif|[[/]] Double}}\n!\n!\n!\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Etymologies]]\n[[Category:Hieroglyphs| ]]\n[[Category:Egyptian inventions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pictographic sign}}\n{{other uses}}\n[[File:Egypt Hieroglyphe4.jpg|right|260px|thumb|Egyptian hieroglyphs typical of the Graeco-Roman period, sculpted in [[Relief]].<br>Glyphs: [[Viper (hieroglyph)|viper]], [[Owl (hieroglyph)|Owl\n]], [[Bread bun (hieroglyph)|'bread bun']], [[Folded cloth (s hieroglyph)|folded cloth]] ]]\nA '''hieroglyph''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]] for \"sacred carvings\") was a [[Character (symbol)|character]] of the [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|ancient Egyptian writing system]]. [[logogram|Logographic]] scripts that are pictographic in form in a way reminiscent of ancient Egyptian are also sometimes called \"hieroglyphs\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Egypt, Ancient: Hieroglyphics and Origins of Alphabet|url=http://www.credoreference.com/entry/routafricanhistory/egypt_ancient_hieroglyphics_and_origins_of_alphabet|publisher=Encyclopedia of African History Title information {{Subscription required|via=[[Credo Reference]]}}|accessdate=12 September 2012|date=}}</ref> In [[Neoplatonism]], especially during the [[Renaissance]], a \"hieroglyph\" was an artistic representation of an [[esoteric]] idea, which Neoplatonists believed actual Egyptian hieroglyphs to be. The word ''hieroglyphics'' refer to a hieroglyphic script. \n\nThe Egyptians invented the [[pictorial]] [[Writing system|script]]. The appearance of these distinctive figures in 3000 BCE marked the beginning of Egyptian [[civilization]]. Though based on images, Egyptian script was more than a sophisticated form of picture-writing. Each picture/[[glyph]] served three functions: (1) to represent the image of a thing or action, (2) to stand for the sound of a [[syllable]], and (3) to clarify the precise meaning of adjoining glyphs. Writing hieroglyphs required some artistic skill, limiting the number chosen to learn it.<ref>The Alphabet Versus the Goddess, by Leonard Shlain</ref> Only those privileged with an extensive education (i.e. the [[Pharaoh]], [[nobility]] and [[priest]]s) were able to read and write hieroglyphs; others used simpler 'joined-up' versions: [[Demotic (Egyptian)|demotic]] and [[hieratic]] script.\n\n==List of scripts and script-like systems sometimes labeled 'hieroglyphic'==\n* [[Anatolian hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Aztec hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Chukchi language#Orthography|Chukchi hieroglyphs]] (see [[Tenevil]])\n* [[Cretan hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Egyptian hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Mayan hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Mi'kmaq hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Muisca art#Hieroglyphs|Muisca hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Ojibwe writing systems#Ojibwe \"hieroglyphs\"|Ojibwe hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Olmec hieroglyphs]]\n* [[Chinese characters]]\n\nOne of the two forms of the [[Meroitic alphabet|Meroitic writing system]] is usually described as \"Meroitic hieroglyphs\" because the characters are similar to and in most cases derived from Egyptian hieroglyphs. They are used, however, not as logographs but as an [[Abugida|alphasyllabary]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of languages by writing system]]\n* [[Monas Hieroglyphica]]\n* [[Mother Goose in Hieroglyphics]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title= [[Middle Egyptian: An Introduction to the Language and Culture of Hieroglyphs]]|last=Allen|first=James P.|authorlink=James Peter Allen|year=2001 |publisher= Cambridge University Press|location=New York|isbn= 9780521774833|oclc=51226851}}\n*{{cite book |title=Egypt and the Egyptians|last1= Brewer|first1=Douglas J.|last2=Teeter|first2=Emily|year= 2007|publisher= Cambridge University Press|location= Cambridge|isbn=9780521851503 |oclc=433993212}}\n*{{cite book |title= [[Ancient Egyptian Hieroglyphs: A Practical Guide]]|last=Kamrin|first=Janice|year=2004|publisher= Harry N. Abrams|location= New York|isbn=9780810949614 |oclc=55019226}}\n*{{cite book |title= The Story of Writing: Alphabets, Hieroglyphs & Pictograms |last= Robinson |first=Andrew |year=2007 |publisher= Thames & Hudson |location= London |isbn= 978-050028660-9 |oclc= 172818065}}\n\n{{Commons category|Hieroglyphs}}\n{{wiktionary|hieroglyph|hieroglyphic}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!{{Serif|<hiero>\nm:n\nSA\nSA\nm:a\n</hiero>}}{{Serif|[[/]] Double}}\n!\n!\n!\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Etymologies]]\n[[Category:Hieroglyphs| ]]\n[[Category:Egyptian inventions]]\n", "name_user": "49.145.141.85", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hieroglyph"}
{"title_page": "Sabina Hidalgo", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican dancer and singer}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Sabina Hidalgo Pa\u00f1o''', (born on September 20, 1999) professionally known as Sabina Hidalgo, is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] dancer and singer. Representing [[Mexico]], she is part of the global pop group, [[Now United]]. {{Infobox person\n| name               = Sabina Hidalgo\n| birth_date         = September 20, 1999 (age 20)\n| birth_place        = [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], Mexico\n| nationality        = Mexican\n| occupation         = {{Hlist|Singer | dancer}}\n| years_active       = 2017-present\n| agent              = [[XIX Entertainment]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}\n| height             = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}\n| partner            = Pepe Gonz\u00e1lez\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n  |background = solo_singer\n  |genre = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[World music|world]]}}\n  |instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]] \n  |label = [[XIX Entertainment]]\n  |years_active = 2017\u2013present\n  |associated_acts = [[Now United]]\n  }}\n}}\n== Early Life ==\nHidalgo was born in [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], [[Mexico]]. At the age of 5, Hidalgo's parents enrolled her in ballet classes, since then she fell in love with dancing. She later started taking jazz, hip hop and other forms of dance<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gentebien.com.mx/perfiles/perfiles/sabina-hidalgo-12351|title=Sabina Hidalgo|last=Informador|first=El|website=Gente Bien|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n== Career ==\nAt age 16, Hidalgo was living in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] when she was contacted through the app, [[musical.ly]] to audition for a new group created by [[Simon Fuller]]. She sent in a couple of dancing videos and after six months, she was contacted through her [[Instagram]] to send in more videos. A week later, in Cancun - she auditioned on camera, finally passing to the final stages. She along with two other representatives for Mexico (including fellow member Joalin Loukamaa), were sent to Los Angeles for a week-long bootcamp - finally being chosen as the Mexican representative for Now United.\n\n== Personal life ==\nSabina Hidalgo has one dog named Lola, gifted by her boyfriend. She is currently dating Mexican soccer player, Pepe Gonz\u00e1lez, member of Leones Negros league.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Now United ===\n{{For|Sabina's work with [[Now United]]|Now United#Discography}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican dancer and singer}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Sabina Hidalgo Pa\u00f1o''', (born on September 20, 1999) professionally known as Sabina Hidalgo, is a [[Mexican]] dancer and singer. Representing [[Mexico]], she is part of the global pop group, [[Now United]]. {{Infobox person\n| name               = Sabina Hidalgo\n| birth_date         = September 20, 1999 (age 20)\n| birth_place        = [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], Mexico\n| nationality        = Mexican\n| occupation         = {{Hlist|Singer | dancer}}\n| years_active       = 2017-present\n| agent              = [[XIX Entertainment]] {{small|(2017\u2013present)}}\n| height             = {{height|ft=5|in=8}}\n| partner            = Pepe Gonz\u00e1lez\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n  |background = solo_singer\n  |genre = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[World music|world]]}}\n  |instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]] \n  |label = [[XIX Entertainment]]\n  |years_active = 2017\u2013present\n  |associated_acts = [[Now United]]\n  }}\n}}\n== Early Life ==\nHidalgo was born in [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], [[Mexico]]. At the age of 5, Hidalgo's parents enrolled her in ballet classes, since then she fell in love with dancing. She later started taking jazz, hip hop and other forms of dance<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gentebien.com.mx/perfiles/perfiles/sabina-hidalgo-12351|title=Sabina Hidalgo|last=Informador|first=El|website=Gente Bien|language=es|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n== Career ==\nAt age 16, Hidalgo was living in [[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]] when she was contacted through the app, [[musical.ly]] to audition for a new group created by [[Simon Fuller]]. She sent in a couple of dancing videos and after six months, she was contacted through her [[Instagram]] to send in more videos. A week later, in Cancun - she auditioned on camera, finally passing to the final stages. She along with two other representatives for Mexico (including fellow member Joalin Loukamaa), were sent to Los Angeles for a week-long bootcamp - finally being chosen as the Mexican representative for Now United.\n\n== Personal life ==\nSabina Hidalgo has one dog named Lola, gifted by her boyfriend. She is currently dating Mexican soccer player, Pepe Gonz\u00e1lez, member of Leones Negros league.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Now United ===\n{{For|Sabina's work with [[Now United]]|Now United#Discography}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican singers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMexican(link changed toMexicans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabina_Hidalgo"}
{"title_page": "Peder Anker (historian)", "text_new": "{{about|the historian|the businessman and politician|Peder Anker}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Peder Anker\n| image             = <!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File: Peder Anker.png|thumb|upright=1.4]] -->\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = Peder Anker, 2009\n| birth_date        = <!-- {{Birth date|1966|05|26}} -->\n| birth_place       = [[Oslo, Norway]]\n| fields            = History of Ecology, [[Environmental Science]], Ecological Architecture and Design, [[Philosophy]]\n| alma_mater        = [[Harvard University]], [[University of Oslo]]\n| known_for         = \"The Power of the Periphery: How Norway Became an Environmental Pioneer for the World,\" Cambridge University Press, 2020.\n| website           = {{URL| http://pederanker.com/ }}\n}}\n'''Peder Anker''' (pronounced /PAY-dur anchor/; born May 27, 1966, in [[Oslo, Norway]]) is a [[historian]] of [[environmental sciences]], specializing in the history of [[ecology]] and ecological architecture and design. Anker is currently an associate professor at the [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]] at [[New York University]].<ref name=\"nyu.academia\">{{cite web|last=Anker |first=Peder |url=https://nyu.academia.edu/PederAnker |title=Peder Anker &#124; New York University - Academia.edu |publisher=Nyu.academia.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\nAnker has received research fellowships from the [[Fulbright Program]], the [[Dibner Institute]] and the [[Max Planck Institute for the History of Science]], and been a visiting scholar at both [[Columbia University]] and [[University of Oslo]].\n\nHe is the author of ''From Bauhaus to Eco-House: A History of Ecological Design'' ([[Louisiana State University]] Press 2010), which explores the intersection of [[architecture]] and [[ecological science]], and ''Imperial Ecology: Environmental Order in the British Empire, 1895-1945'' ([[Harvard University]] Press, 2001), which investigates how the promising new science of [[ecology]] flourished in the [[British Empire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pederanker.com/about/ |title=About |publisher=Peder Anker |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>http://gallatin.nyu.edu/academics/faculty/pja7.html</ref> His upcoming book, ''[https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/history/environmental-history/power-periphery-how-norway-became-environmental-pioneer-world?format=HB The Power of The Periphery]'', will be released in 2020. This interdisciplinary piece explores the history of environmental sciences in Norway from the publishing of [[Rachel Carson]]\u2019s ''[[Silent Spring]]'' until the [[Earth Summit|Rio Conference]] in 1992.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nPeder Anker was born in [[Oslo, Norway]]. His mother, Bodil Borchsenius Anker, was a high-school teacher and researcher of pedagogy at the [[University of Oslo]], while his father, Erik Anker, was a partner at the architectural office Anker & H\u00f8laas. Peder attended the Rudolf Steiner-school and Persbraaten High School, both in Oslo. His older brother Espen Anker is a practicing [[psychiatrist]] while his younger sister Hedevig Anker is an artist. Peder has been married to Nina Edwards Anker since 2001. They have two children, Lukas and Theo.\n\n== Education ==\n\nAnker earned a B.A. in Environmental Philosophy in 1991 from the [[University of Oslo]], a M.A. in [[Philosophy]] in 1993 from the [[University of Oslo]], a M.A. in [[History of Science]] in 1998 from [[Harvard University]], and a Ph.D. in [[History of Science]] in 1999 from [[Harvard University]].<ref name=\"pederanker\">{{cite web|url=http://pederanker.com/about/cv/ |title=CV |publisher=Peder Anker |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nAnker started his academic career at the [[University of Oslo]], where he was a lecturer at the Department of [[Philosophy]] from 1993 to 1994. After receiving his Ph.D., he became a research fellow at the Department of [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Oslo]] in 2000.<ref name=\"pederanker\" /> He then taught at [[Harvard University]], in the Department of [[History of Science]] from 2000 to 2001. During this time, he published his first book, [http://pederanker.com/imperial-ecology/ ''Imperial Ecology: Environmental Order in the British Empire, 1895-1945'']. From here, he conducted Postdoctoral Research at the Center for Development and Environment at the [[University of Oslo]] until 2006. From 2006 to 2009, he continued at the [[University of Oslo]] where he was a [[research fellow]] for the Forum for the University History. Anker is currently an [[associate professor]] at The [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]] at [[New York University]].<ref name=\"nyu.academia\" /> While working at The [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]], he co-founded [http://gdnyu.com/ GLOBAL Design NYU], and is currently working as [http://www.gdnyu.com/people.html GDNYU Director] along with [[Mitchell Joachim]] and [[Louise Harpman]].<ref>{{cite web|author=mitchell joachim |url=http://www.gdnyu.com/people.html |title=Global Design New York University |publisher=Gdnyu.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref> While at [[New York University]], he published [http://pederanker.com/bauhaus/ ''From Bauhaus to Ecohouse: A History of Ecological Design''] and ''[https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/history/environmental-history/power-periphery-how-norway-became-environmental-pioneer-world?format=HB The Power of The Periphery]''. For his work in [[environmentalism]], Anker was interviewed by [[Adam Curtis]] for a [[BBC TV]] Documentary, \u201cHow the \u2018ecosystem\u2019 myth has been used for sinister means.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pederanker.com/category/publications/books/ |title=Books |publisher=Peder Anker |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>http://pederanker.com/2011/06/03/peder-anker-in-the-use-and-abuse-of-vegetational-concepts/</ref>\nIn 1995-1999, Anker participated in the Fulbright-Hays Fellowship Program, Bertram and [[Barbara Cohn]] Fellowship at [[Harvard University]],  and was a [[Dibner Institute]] Graduate Fellow at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"pederanker\" />\n\n==Selected works==\n* \"[https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/history/environmental-history/power-periphery-how-norway-became-environmental-pioneer-world?format=HB The Power of the Periphery: How Norway Became an Environmental Pioneer for the World],\" Cambridge University Press, 2020.\n\n* \u201cComputing Environmental Design,\u201d ''[https://www.routledge.com/Computer-Architectures-Constructing-the-Common-Ground/Vardouli-Touloumi/p/book/9780815396529 Computer Architectures: Constructing the Common Ground], 1945-1980,'' Theodora Vardouli and Olga Touloumi (eds.), (London: Routledge, 2019), 15-34.\n\n* \u201c[http://averyreview.com/issues/29/anthropocene-architecture Anthropocene Architecture: Design Earth\u2019s Geostories]\u201d with Nina Edwards Anker, The Avery Review 29 (Feb. 2018).\n* Republished in: Rania Ghosn and El Hadi Jazairy, ''[http://actar.com/product/geostories/ Geostories]: Another Architecture for the Environment'', (Barcelona: Actar, 2018), 206-213.\n* \u201c[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10584-016-1653-x A pioneer country? A history of Norwegian climate politics]\u201d Climatic Change, (Online March 2016), 1-13. [https://link.springer.com/journal/10584/151/1/page/1 Journal edition 151:1] (2018), 29-41.\n\n* \"Global Design: Elsewhere Envisioned\", with Mitchell Joachim and Louise Harpman. (Munich: Prestel, 2014).\n* \u201cThe Call for a New Ecotheology in Norway,\u201d ''[[Journal for the Study of Religion, Nature and Culture]]'' 7:2 (2013), 187\u2013207. \n* \u201cEcological Communication at the Oxford Imperial Forestry Institute,\u201d in Cultivating the Colonies: Colonial States and their Environmental Legacies, Christina Folke Ax (et.a.) (ed.) Ohio University Press, 2011. \n* \u201cViewing the Earth from Without or from Within\u201d with Nina Edwards Anker, New Geographies 4 (2011), 89\u201394.\n* \"Seeing Pink: The Eco-Art of Simon Starling,\" Journal of Visual Art Practice 7 (2008), 3\u20139.\n* \"Deep Ecology in Bucharest,\" Trumpeter 24 (2008), 56\u201358.\n* \"Science as a Vacation: A History of Ecology in Norway,\"  History of Science, 45:4 (2007), 455\u2013479.\n* \"Buckminster Fuller as Captain of Spaceship Earth,\" Minerva, 45:4 (2007), 417\u2013434.\n* \"Graphic Language: Herbert Bayer\u2019s Environmental Design,\" Environmental History, 12:2 (2007), 254\u2013279.\n* \"The Closed World of Ecological Architecture,\" The Journal of Architecture, 10:5 (2005), 527\u2013552.\n* \"The Bauhaus of Nature,\" Modernism/Modernity, 12:2 (2005), 229\u2013251.\n* \"The Ecological Colonization of Space,\" Environmental History, 10:2 (2005), 239\u2013268.\n* \"A Vindication of the Rights of Brutes,\" Philosophy and Geography, 7:2 (2004), 261\u2013266.\n* \"The Economy of Nature in the Botany of Nehemiah Grew,\" Archives of Natural History, 31:2 (2004), 191\u2013207.\n* \"The Politics of Ecology in South Africa on the Radical Left,\" Journal of the History of Biology, 37:2 (2004), 303\u2013331.\n* \"The Philosopher\u2019s Cabin and the Household of Nature,\" Ethics, Place and Environment, 6:2 (2003), 131\u2013141.\n* \"The Context of Ecosystem Theory,\" Ecosystems, 5:7 (2002), 611\u2013613.\n* \"The Dream of the Biocentric community and the Structure of Utopias,\" with Nina Witoszek, Worldviews, 2 (1998), 239\u2013256.\n\n== Accolades ==\n* [http://www.nysca.org/ New York State Council on the Arts Design Award] (with Nina Edwards), 2003.\n* [http://pederanker.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/fhhs-citation-2000.png Forum for History of Human Science], Dissertation Prize, 2000. \n* Harvard University Certificate of Distinction in Teaching, [https://web.archive.org/web/20130329122855/http://bokcenter.harvard.edu/icb/icb.do Derek Bok Center], 1997.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://pederanker.com/ Peder Anker Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anker, Peder}}\n[[Category:Norwegian historians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:New York University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Oslo]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the historian|the businessman and politician|Peder Anker}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Peder Anker\n| image             = <!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File: Peder Anker.png|thumb|upright=1.4]] -->\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = Peder Anker, 2009\n| birth_date        = <!-- {{Birth date|1966|05|26}} -->\n| birth_place       = [[Oslo, Norway]]\n| fields            = History of Ecology, [[Environmental Science]], Ecological Architecture and Design, [[Philosophy]]\n| alma_mater        = [[Harvard University]], [[University of Oslo]]\n| known_for         = \"The Power of the Periphery: How Norway Became an Environmental Pioneer for the World,\" Cambridge University Press, 2020.\n| website           = {{URL| http://pederanker.com/ }}\n}}\n'''Peder Anker''' (pronounced /PAY-dur anchor/; born May 27, 1966, in [[Oslo, Norway]]) is a [[historian]] of [[environmental sciences]], specializing in the history of [[ecology]] and ecological architecture and design. Anker is currently an associate professor at the [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]] at [[New York University]].<ref name=\"nyu.academia\">{{cite web|last=Anker |first=Peder |url=https://nyu.academia.edu/PederAnker |title=Peder Anker &#124; New York University - Academia.edu |publisher=Nyu.academia.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\nAnker has received research fellowships from the [[Fulbright Program]], the [[Dibner Institute]] and the [[Max Planck Institute for the History of Science]], and been a visiting scholar at both [[Columbia University]] and [[University of Oslo]].\n\nHe is the author of ''From Bauhaus to Eco-House: A History of Ecological Design'' ([[Louisiana State University]] Press 2010), which explores the intersection of [[architecture]] and [[ecological science]], and ''Imperial Ecology: Environmental Order in the British Empire, 1895-1945'' ([[Harvard University]] Press, 2001), which investigates how the promising new science of [[ecology]] flourished in the [[British Empire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pederanker.com/about/ |title=About |publisher=Peder Anker |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>http://gallatin.nyu.edu/academics/faculty/pja7.html</ref> His upcoming book, ''[https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/history/environmental-history/power-periphery-how-norway-became-environmental-pioneer-world?format=HB The Power of The Periphery]'', will be released in 2020. This interdisciplinary piece explores the history of environmental sciences in Norway from the publishing of [[Rachel Carson]]\u2019s ''[[Silent Spring]]'' until the [[Earth Summit|Rio Conference]] in 1992.\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nPeder Anker was born in [[Oslo, Norway]]. His mother, Bodil Borchsenius Anker, was a high-school teacher and researcher of pedagogy at the [[University of Oslo]], while his father, Erik Anker, was a partner at the architectural office Anker & H\u00f8laas. Peder attended the Rudolf Steiner-school and Persbraaten High School, both in Oslo. His older brother Espen Anker is a practicing [[psychiatrist]] while his younger sister Hedevig Anker is an artist. Peder has been married to Nina Edwards Anker since 2001. They have two children, Lukas and Theo.\n\n== Education ==\n\nAnker earned a B.A. in Environmental Philosophy in 1991 from the [[University of Oslo]], a M.A. in [[Philosophy]] in 1993 from the [[University of Oslo]], a M.A. in [[History of Science]] in 1998 from [[Harvard University]], and a Ph.D. in [[History of Science]] in 1999 from [[Harvard University]].<ref name=\"pederanker\">{{cite web|url=http://pederanker.com/about/cv/ |title=CV |publisher=Peder Anker |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nAnker started his academic career at the [[University of Oslo]], where he was a lecturer at the Department of [[Philosophy]] from 1993 to 1994. After receiving his Ph.D., he became a research fellow at the Department of [[Philosophy]] at the [[University of Oslo]] in 2000.<ref name=\"pederanker\" /> He then taught at [[Harvard University]], in the Department of [[History of Science]] from 2000 to 2001. During this time, he published his first book, [http://pederanker.com/imperial-ecology/ ''Imperial Ecology: Environmental Order in the British Empire, 1895-1945'']. From here, he conducted Postdoctoral Research at the Center for Development and Environment at the [[University of Oslo]] until 2006. From 2006 to 2009, he continued at the [[University of Oslo]] where he was a [[research fellow]] for the Forum for the University History. Anker is currently an [[associate professor]] at The [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]] at [[New York University]].<ref name=\"nyu.academia\" /> While working at The [[Gallatin School of Individualized Study]], he co-founded [http://gdnyu.com/ GLOBAL Design NYU], and is currently working as [http://www.gdnyu.com/people.html GDNYU Director] along with [[Mitchell Joachim]] and [[Louise Harpman]].<ref>{{cite web|author=mitchell joachim |url=http://www.gdnyu.com/people.html |title=Global Design New York University |publisher=Gdnyu.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref> While at [[New York University]], he published [http://pederanker.com/bauhaus/ ''From Bauhaus to Ecohouse: A History of Ecological Design''] and ''[https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/history/environmental-history/power-periphery-how-norway-became-environmental-pioneer-world?format=HB The Power of The Periphery]''. For his work in [[environmentalism]], Anker was interviewed by [[Adam Curtis]] for a [[BBC TV]] Documentary, \u201cHow the \u2018ecosystem\u2019 myth has been used for sinister means.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pederanker.com/category/publications/books/ |title=Books |publisher=Peder Anker |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref><ref>http://pederanker.com/2011/06/03/peder-anker-in-the-use-and-abuse-of-vegetational-concepts/</ref>\nIn 1995-1999, Anker participated in the Fulbright-Hays Fellowship Program, Bertram and [[Barbara Cohn]] Fellowship at [[Harvard University]],  and was a [[Dibner Institute]] Graduate Fellow at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref name=\"pederanker\" />\n\n==Selected works==\n* \"[https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/history/environmental-history/power-periphery-how-norway-became-environmental-pioneer-world?format=HB The Power of the Periphery: How Norway Became an Environmental Pioneer for the World],\" Cambridge University Press, 2020.\n\n''In this innovative, interdisciplinary history, Anker explores the ways in which ecological concerns were imported via Rachel Carson\u2019s Silent Spring in 1962, then to be exported from Norway back to the world at the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992.''\n\n* \u201cComputing Environmental Design,\u201d ''[https://www.routledge.com/Computer-Architectures-Constructing-the-Common-Ground/Vardouli-Touloumi/p/book/9780815396529 Computer Architectures: Constructing the Common Ground], 1945-1980,'' Theodora Vardouli and Olga Touloumi (eds.), (London: Routledge, 2019), 15-34.\n\n''Anker's paper interrogates the emergence of complexity as an aesthetic and design problem, formative for the introduction of computing to architectural design.''\n\n* \u201c[http://averyreview.com/issues/29/anthropocene-architecture Anthropocene Architecture: Design Earth\u2019s Geostories]\u201d with Nina Edwards Anker, The Avery Review 29 (Feb. 2018).\n* Republished in: Rania Ghosn and El Hadi Jazairy, ''[http://actar.com/product/geostories/ Geostories]: Another Architecture for the Environment'', (Barcelona: Actar, 2018), 206-213.\n* \u201c[https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10584-016-1653-x A pioneer country? A history of Norwegian climate politics]\u201d Climatic Change, (Online March 2016), 1-13. [https://link.springer.com/journal/10584/151/1/page/1 Journal edition 151:1] (2018), 29-41.\n\n* \"Global Design: Elsewhere Envisioned\", with Mitchell Joachim and Louise Harpman. (Munich: Prestel, 2014).\n* \u201cThe Call for a New Ecotheology in Norway,\u201d ''[[Journal for the Study of Religion, Nature and Culture]]'' 7:2 (2013), 187\u2013207. \n* \u201cEcological Communication at the Oxford Imperial Forestry Institute,\u201d in Cultivating the Colonies: Colonial States and their Environmental Legacies, Christina Folke Ax (et.a.) (ed.) Ohio University Press, 2011. \n* \u201cViewing the Earth from Without or from Within\u201d with Nina Edwards Anker, New Geographies 4 (2011), 89\u201394.\n* \"Seeing Pink: The Eco-Art of Simon Starling,\" Journal of Visual Art Practice 7 (2008), 3\u20139.\n* \"Deep Ecology in Bucharest,\" Trumpeter 24 (2008), 56\u201358.\n* \"Science as a Vacation: A History of Ecology in Norway,\"  History of Science, 45:4 (2007), 455\u2013479.\n* \"Buckminster Fuller as Captain of Spaceship Earth,\" Minerva, 45:4 (2007), 417\u2013434.\n* \"Graphic Language: Herbert Bayer\u2019s Environmental Design,\" Environmental History, 12:2 (2007), 254\u2013279.\n* \"The Closed World of Ecological Architecture,\" The Journal of Architecture, 10:5 (2005), 527\u2013552.\n* \"The Bauhaus of Nature,\" Modernism/Modernity, 12:2 (2005), 229\u2013251.\n* \"The Ecological Colonization of Space,\" Environmental History, 10:2 (2005), 239\u2013268.\n* \"A Vindication of the Rights of Brutes,\" Philosophy and Geography, 7:2 (2004), 261\u2013266.\n* \"The Economy of Nature in the Botany of Nehemiah Grew,\" Archives of Natural History, 31:2 (2004), 191\u2013207.\n* \"The Politics of Ecology in South Africa on the Radical Left,\" Journal of the History of Biology, 37:2 (2004), 303\u2013331.\n* \"The Philosopher\u2019s Cabin and the Household of Nature,\" Ethics, Place and Environment, 6:2 (2003), 131\u2013141.\n* \"The Context of Ecosystem Theory,\" Ecosystems, 5:7 (2002), 611\u2013613.\n* \"The Dream of the Biocentric community and the Structure of Utopias,\" with Nina Witoszek, Worldviews, 2 (1998), 239\u2013256.\n\n== Accolades ==\n* [http://www.nysca.org/ New York State Council on the Arts Design Award] (with Nina Edwards), 2003.\n* [http://pederanker.files.wordpress.com/2012/09/fhhs-citation-2000.png Forum for History of Human Science], Dissertation Prize, 2000. \n* Harvard University Certificate of Distinction in Teaching, [https://web.archive.org/web/20130329122855/http://bokcenter.harvard.edu/icb/icb.do Derek Bok Center], 1997.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://pederanker.com/ Peder Anker Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anker, Peder}}\n[[Category:Norwegian historians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:New York University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo faculty]]\n[[Category:Writers from Oslo]]\n", "name_user": "Lma0m0nster", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peder_Anker_(historian)"}
{"title_page": "Louis, duc de La Chastre", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2015}}\n{{Expand French|Claude-Louis de La Ch\u00e2tre|date=April 2015|topic=mil}}\n[[File:Blason fam fr La Ch\u00e2tre.svg|thumb|right|140px|Duke de La Chastre's [[coat of arms]]]]\n\n'''Claude-Louis-Raoul de La Ch\u00e2tre''', otherwise known as '''''Louis, duc de La Chastre''''' (born 30 September 1745; died 13 July 1824) was an [[aristocrat]]ic [[French people|French]] military commander, [[diplomat]] and politician of the 18th and 19th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp65855/claude-louis-duc-de-la-chatre |title=National Portrait Gallery - Person - Claude Louis, duc de la Ch\u00e2tre |publisher=Npg.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThe elder son of [[Lieutenant-General]] Charles-Louis, [[marquis]] de [[La Ch\u00e2tre]] (1724-1793) by his wife Isabelle (1725-1794) daughter of [[:fr:Famille Jouvenel des Ursins|Claude, marquis de Tra\u00eenel]], his relatives included [[Duchess Maria Antonia of Bavaria|Maria Antonia, Duchess of Bavaria and Electress of Saxony]] as well as [[Charles Edward Stuart|Charles Edward Stuart (''The Young Pretender'')]].\n\n[[Style (manner of address)|Styled]] [[Courtesy title|comte de Nan\u00e7ay]] after 1734, he was commissioned as a [[Sous-lieutenant]] in the [[French Royal Army (1652\u20131830)|French Army]] in 1756, becoming a [[Lieutenant]] in the [[:fr:65e r\u00e9giment d'infanterie|R\u00e9giment du Boulonnois]] in 1761, [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] in 1764 and then in 1770 [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[:fr:Corps des Grenadiers de France|in the Grenadiers]]. In 1771 he was seconded as [[Colonel]] of the [[43rd Infantry Regiment (France)|R\u00e9giment de Royal-Vaisseaux]], becoming a [[Gentlemen of the Privy Chamber]] to [[Louis XVIII of France|Prince Louis, comte de Provence]] and in 1774 [[Mestre de camp|Mestre-de-camp]] of the [[:fr:R\u00e9giment des dragons de Monsieur|R\u00e9giment des dragons de Monsieur]]. He was promoted [[Brigadier]] in 1781, [[Mar\u00e9chal-de-camp]] in 1788 and commanded the [[:fr:8e r\u00e9giment de chasseurs \u00e0 cheval|Guyenne Cavalry Regiment]] (1786\u201389).\n\nAfter being appointed [[Bailiff|Royal Bailiff]] of [[Guyenne|Berry]] in 1788, he sat briefly as a [[Deputy (legislator)|deputy]] of the [[Estates-General of 1789|Estates-General]] in 1789.\n\nHis father, the marquis, was guillotined by the Revolutionaries in 1793 (when he succeeded to his father's titles), but La Chastre managed to escape to England where he raised the [[:fr:R\u00e9giment Loyal-\u00c9migrant|R\u00e9giment Loyal-\u00c9migrant]]. Having commanded his troops with distinction throughout the Low Countries, Quiberon and Portugal, he returned to [[London]] in 1807.\n\nHe became the first [[Ambassador|French Ambassador]] to the [[Court of St James's]] under the [[Bourbon Restoration]].\n\nLa Chastre was created a [[peer of France]] (1815) and [[duke]] (1816) by [[King Louis XVIII]], in addition to receiving other honours.\n\nHe was married to [[Comtesse de la Ch\u00e2tre|Marie Charlotte Louise Perrette Agla\u00e9 Bontemps]] from 1778 until their divorce in 1793.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/437900 |title=\u00c9lisabeth Louise Vig\u00e9e Le Brun &#124; Comtesse de la Ch\u00e2tre (Marie Charlotte Louise Perrette Agla\u00e9 Bontemps, 1762\u20131848) &#124; The Metropolitan Museum of Art |publisher=Metmuseum.org |date= |accessdate=2015-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and titles==\n[[File:Order of the Holy Spirit (heraldry).svg|thumb|right|155px|Collar of the [[Order of the Holy Spirit|Saint-Esprit]]]]\n* [[File:Crown of a Duke of France.svg|45px]] [[Duc]] de France\n* [[File:Ordre Royal et Militaire de Saint-Louis Chevalier ribbon.svg|45px]] Grand-croix, [[Ordre de Saint-Louis]] \n* [[File:SMOM-gc.svg|45px]] Chevalier, [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Ordre de Malte]]\n* [[File:Cavaliere SSML BAR.svg|45px]] Chevalier, [[Order of Our Lady of Mount Carmel|Ordres Royaux, Militaires et Hospitaliers de Notre-Dame du Mont-Carmel et de Saint-Lazare de J\u00e9rusalem R\u00e9unis]]\n* [[File:Ordre du Saint-Esprit Chevalier ribbon.svg|45px]] Chevalier, [[Order of the Holy Spirit|Ordre du Saint-Esprit]]\n* [[File:Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|45px]] Officier, [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Ambassadors of France to the United Kingdom]]\n* [[:fr:Maison de La Ch\u00e2tre|Maison de La Ch\u00e2tre]] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.almanachdegotha.org/ Almanachdegotha.org]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Chastre, Louis de}}\n[[Category:1745 births]]\n[[Category:1824 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dukes of La Chastre]]\n[[Category:Knights of Malta]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of Saint Louis]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of France to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:19th-century French diplomats]]\n[[Category:French generals]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Honour]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Peers of the Bourbon Restoration]]\n[[Category:Cavalry commanders]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Holy Spirit]]\n[[Category:French nobility]]\n[[Category:State ministers of France]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2015}}\n{{Expand French|Claude-Louis de La Ch\u00e2tre|date=April 2015|topic=mil}}\n[[File:Blason fam fr La Ch\u00e2tre.svg|thumb|right|140px|Duke de La Chastre's [[coat of arms]]]]\n\n'''Claude-Louis-Raoul de La Ch\u00e2tre''', otherwise known as '''''Louis, duc de La Chastre''''' (born 30 September 1745; died 13 July 1824) was an [[aristocrat]]ic [[French people|French]] military commander, [[diplomat]] and politician of the 18th and 19th centuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp65855/claude-louis-duc-de-la-chatre |title=National Portrait Gallery - Person - Claude Louis, duc de la Ch\u00e2tre |publisher=Npg.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThe elder son of [[Lieutenant-General]] Charles-Louis, [[marquis]] de [[La Ch\u00e2tre]] (1724-1793) by his wife Isabelle (1725-1794) daughter of [[:fr:Famille Jouvenel des Ursins|Claude, marquis de Tra\u00eenel]], his relatives included [[Duchess Maria Antonia of Bavaria|Maria Antonia, Duchess of Bavaria and Electress of Saxony]] as well as [[Charles Edward Stuart|Charles Edward Stuart (''The Young Pretender'')]].\n\n[[Style (manner of address)|Styled]] [[Courtesy title|comte de Nan\u00e7ay]] after 1734, he was commissioned as a [[Sous-lieutenant]] in the [[French Royal Army (1652\u20131830)|French Army]] in 1756, becoming a [[Lieutenant]] in the [[:fr:65e r\u00e9giment d'infanterie|R\u00e9giment du Boulonnois]] in 1761, [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]] in 1764 and then in 1770 [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[:fr:Corps des Grenadiers de France|in the Grenadiers]]. In 1771 he was seconded as [[Colonel]] of the [[43rd Infantry Regiment (France)|R\u00e9giment de Royal-Vaisseaux]], becoming a [[Gentlemen of the Privy Chamber]] to [[Louis XVIII of France|Prince Louis, comte de Provence]] and in 1774 [[Mestre de camp|Mestre-de-camp]] of the [[:fr:R\u00e9giment des dragons de Monsieur|R\u00e9giment des dragons de Monsieur]]. He was promoted [[Brigadier]] in 1781, [[Mar\u00e9chal-de-camp]] in 1788 and commanded the [[:fr:8e r\u00e9giment de chasseurs \u00e0 cheval|Guyenne Cavalry Regiment]] (1786\u201389).\n\nAfter being appointed [[Bailiff|Royal Bailiff]] of [[Guyenne|Berry]] in 1788, he sat briefly as a [[Deputy (legislator)|deputy]] of the [[Estates-General of 1789|Estates-General]] in 1789.\n\nHis father, the marquis, was guillotined by the Revolutionaries in 1793 (when he succeeded to his father's titles), but La Chastre managed to escape to England where he raised the [[:fr:R\u00e9giment Loyal-\u00c9migrant|R\u00e9giment Loyal-\u00c9migrant]]. Having commanded his troops with distinction throughout the Low Countries, Quiberon and Portugal, he returned to [[London]] in 1807.\n\nHe became the first [[Ambassador|French Ambassador]] to the [[Court of St James's]] under the [[Bourbon Restoration]].\n\nLa Chastre was created a [[peer of France]] (1815) and [[duke]] (1816) by [[King Louis XVIII]], in addition to receiving other honours.\n\nHe was married to [[Comtesse de la Ch\u00e2tre|Marie Charlotte Louise Perrette Agla\u00e9 Bontemps]] from 1778 until their divorce in 1793<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/437900 |title=\u00c9lisabeth Louise Vig\u00e9e Le Brun &#124; Comtesse de la Ch\u00e2tre (Marie Charlotte Louise Perrette Agla\u00e9 Bontemps, 1762\u20131848) &#124; The Metropolitan Museum of Art |publisher=Metmuseum.org |date= |accessdate=2015-04-03}}</ref>.\n\n==Honours and titles==\n[[File:Order of the Holy Spirit (heraldry).svg|thumb|right|155px|Collar of the [[Order of the Holy Spirit|Saint-Esprit]]]]\n* [[File:Crown of a Duke of France.svg|45px]] [[Duc]] de France\n* [[File:Ordre Royal et Militaire de Saint-Louis Chevalier ribbon.svg|45px]] Grand-croix, [[Ordre de Saint-Louis]] \n* [[File:SMOM-gc.svg|45px]] Chevalier, [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Ordre de Malte]]\n* [[File:Cavaliere SSML BAR.svg|45px]] Chevalier, [[Order of Our Lady of Mount Carmel|Ordres Royaux, Militaires et Hospitaliers de Notre-Dame du Mont-Carmel et de Saint-Lazare de J\u00e9rusalem R\u00e9unis]]\n* [[File:Ordre du Saint-Esprit Chevalier ribbon.svg|45px]] Chevalier, [[Order of the Holy Spirit|Ordre du Saint-Esprit]]\n* [[File:Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|45px]] Officier, [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Ambassadors of France to the United Kingdom]]\n* [[:fr:Maison de La Ch\u00e2tre|Maison de La Ch\u00e2tre]] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.almanachdegotha.org/ Almanachdegotha.org]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Chastre, Louis de}}\n[