=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3830257/?ref_=tt_cl_t2|title=Internet Movie Database|date=March 10, 2020 |website=[[IMDB]] |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name|3830257}}\n\n{{SNLCurrentCast}}\n{{America's Got Talent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Villasenor, Melissa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from California]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:American impressionists (entertainers)]]\n[[Category:American sketch comedians]]\n[[Category:American stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American women comedians]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Whittier, California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMexican(link changed toMexicans) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melissa_Villase%C3%B1or"}
{"title_page": "Paramilitary punishment attacks in Northern Ireland", "text_new": "{{short description|Informal criminal justice system operated by loyalist and republican groups in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Use British English Oxford spelling|date=November 2019}}\n[[File:Dublin Road, Belfast, March 2010 (02).JPG|thumb|upright=1.2|alt=A street at night|Many of the attacks have taken place in Belfast at night.]]\nSince the early 1970s, extrajudicial '''punishment attacks''' have been carried out by [[Ulster loyalist]] and [[Irish republican]] paramilitary groups in [[Northern Ireland]]. Attacks can range from a warning or expulsion from Northern Ireland, backed up by the threat of violence, to severe beatings that leave victims in hospital and shootings in the limbs (such as [[kneecapping]]). The cause of the attacks is disputed; proposed explanations include the breakdown of order as a result of the [[Northern Ireland conflict]] ({{circa|1970}}\u20131998), ideological opposition to British law enforcement (in the case of republicans), and the ineffectiveness of police to prevent crime. \n\nSince reporting began in 1973, more than 6,106 shootings and beatings have been reported to the police,  leading to at least 115 deaths. The official figures are an underestimate because many attacks are not reported. Most victims are young men and boys under the age of thirty years, whom their attackers claim are responsible for criminal or antisocial behaviour. Despite attempts to put an end to the practice, according to researcher Sharon Mallon in a 2017 policy briefing, \"paramilitaries are continuing to operate an informal criminal justice system,  with  a  degree  of  political  and  legal  impunity\".{{sfn|Mallon|2017|p=8}}\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n==Name==\nThe term \"punishment\" is controversial. According to [[Liam Kennedy (historian)|Liam Kennedy]], \"Not only has the label 'punishment' a euphemistic quality when applied to extremely cruel practices, it also carries a presumption that the victim is somehow deserving of what he (occasionally she) receives.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Kennedy|1995|p=86}}, cited in {{harvnb|Human Rights Watch|1997|loc=5. Paramilitary \"Policing\", fn 224}}.</ref> In a 2001 debate in the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]], [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland|Alliance]] MLA [[Eileen Bell]] stated, \"I am appalled at the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]]\u2019s use of the term 'punishment beatings'. The use of the term 'punishment' confers on the act a degree of legitimacy by suggesting that the guilt of a victim is an established fact.\"<ref name=\"theyworkforyou\" /> According to the [[Independent Monitoring Commission]], the term \"punishment beating\" \"lends a spurious respectability to the perpetrators, as if they were entitled to take the law into their own hands\".{{sfn|Gallaher|2011|p=10}} [[Families Against Intimidation and Terror]] refers to the attacks as \"mutilation\" rather than \"punishment\".{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=14}} \"Paramilitary policing\" is an alternative term used by some sources.{{sfn|Conway|1997|p=109}}{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1997|p=48}} \"Internal housekeeping\" is a euphemism, coined by Northern Ireland secretary [[Mo Mowlam]] in 1999.{{sfn|Gallaher|2011|p=9}}\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Northern Ireland conflict}}\n[[File:Map of Ireland's capitals.png|thumb|The [[partition of Ireland]]]]\nFrom  the late 1960s to 1998, the [[Northern Ireland conflict]] (also known as the Troubles), was a civil war between [[Irish republican]] groups, who wanted [[Northern Ireland]] to  leave the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United Ireland|unite]] with the [[Republic of Ireland]], and [[Ulster loyalist]] groups, who wanted Northern Ireland to [[Irish unionism|remain part of the UK]].{{sfn|Steinberg|2019|pp=79, 82}}{{sfn|Stevenson|1996|p=126}} The origin of the conflict occurred during the [[Irish revolutionary period]] of the early twentieth century, during which most of Ireland seceded from the UK and became the [[Irish Free State]], while the northern six counties opted to remain under the terms of the [[Anglo-Irish Treaty]].{{sfn|Steinberg|2019|p=81}} The [[Irish republican movement]] considers itself the legitimate successor of the [[Irish Republic]] of 1919 to 1921.{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=10}} Irish republicans do not recognize the [[partition of Ireland|partition]] and consider ongoing [[British rule in Ireland]] to be a foreign [[military occupation|occupation]].{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=151}}{{sfn|Brooks|2019|p=211}} \n\nThe [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) was the largest republican paramilitaries group, while smaller groups include the [[Irish National Liberation Army]]<ref name=\"post\" /> and the [[Official IRA]].{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|p=38}} All three ceased military activity during the [[Northern Ireland peace process]], which led to the 1998 [[Good Friday Agreement]], the official end of the conflict. However, [[dissident republicans]]\u2014such as the [[Real IRA]] and the [[Continuity IRA]]\u2014do not recognize the peace agreement and wage an [[dissident Irish Republican campaign|ongoing campaign]].<ref name=\"times\" /> The [[Ulster Defence Association]] (UDA) and [[Ulster Volunteer Force]] (UVF) are rival groups{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|p=40}} that are responsible for the majority of loyalist murders during the Troubles, while smaller loyalist groups include the [[Red Hand Commando]],<ref name=\"post\" /> [[Ulster Freedom Fighters]] (UFF), and [[Loyalist Volunteer Force]] (LVF).{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|p=43}} Both republican and loyalist groups consider punishment attacks separate from military activity{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=536}} and continue to carry them out while on ceasefire status.<ref name=\"post\" /><ref name=\"times\" />\n\n[[File:Collusion is not an illusion.jpg|thumb|A republican mural in Belfast accusing security forces of collusion]]\nBritish troops were [[Operation Banner|deployed in Northern Ireland]] from 1969  to 2007.{{sfn|Murphy|2009|p=34}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Oliver |first1=Mark |title=Operation Banner, 1969-2007 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jul/31/northernireland.military1 |accessdate=27 November 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=31 July 2007}}</ref> The [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]] (RUC)  was an armed force that took a military approach to [[counter-terrorism]],{{sfn|Murphy|2009|p=38}} had been drawn into pro-unionist [[sectarianism]],{{sfn|Murphy|2009|pp=34\u201335}} [[The Troubles#Collusion between security forces and paramilitaries|colluded with loyalist groups]],{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=136}} and committed [[Five techniques|police brutality, including beatings of suspects]].{{sfn|Murphy|2009|pp=34\u201335}} Real and perceived human rights violations by security forces\u2014including [[Internment in Northern Ireland|internment without trial]], [[Diplock court|special court]]s for political offences, the use of [[plastic bullets]] by riot police, and alleged [[Shoot-to-kill policy in Northern Ireland|shoot-to-kill policy]]\u2014further sapped the state's legitimacy for nationalists.{{sfn|Murphy|2009|p=38}}{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=85}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=155}} In many neighborhoods, the RUC was  so focused  on terrorism that  it neglected ordinary policing, regular patrols, and non-political crime.  Both nationalist and unionist communities complained that the RUC did not respond quickly enough to calls relating to petty crime, and that suspects were pressured to inform on paramilitaries.{{sfn|Human Rights Watch|1997|loc=5. Paramilitary \"Policing\": Introduction}}{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1997|p=48}}\n\nSince the replacement of the RUC with the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] (PSNI) in 2001,{{sfn|Murphy|2009|p=45}}{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=1}} trust has improved, with more than 70% in both communities having a positive assessment of  the PSNI's performance.{{sfn|Bradford ''et al.''|2018|p=2}} However, in many republican neighbourhoods identity has been shaped by distrust of the authorities,{{sfn|Bradford ''et al.''|2018|p=4}} with one republican neighbourhood in West Belfast reporting only 35% trust in the police.{{sfn|Bradford ''et al.''|2018|p=2}} Since the 1985 [[Anglo-Irish Agreement]]{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1997|pp=48\u201349}} and the disbanding of the RUC, trust is decreasing in some loyalist communities.{{sfn|Bradford ''et al.''|2018|p=2}} Among the complaints are  harassment by security forces,{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1997|p=49}} the ineffectiveness of the police, and perceived leniency of sentences meted out by British courts.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=51}}\n\n==Origins==\nIrish nationalist movements have a long history of establishing [[alternative law in Ireland|alternative legal systems]], especially the land courts of the [[Land War]] and the [[D\u00e1il Courts]] during the Anglo-Irish War.{{sfn|Munck|1984|pp=82\u201383}}{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=41\u201343}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=152}} In Northern Ireland, the alternative justice system survived partition and continued into the first years of the Northern Ireland polity.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=152}} Following partition, loyalist militias patrolled parts of the border with the Irish Free State and, in [[Belfast]], the [[Ulster Unionist Labour Association]] set up an unofficial police force in the 1920s.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=153}}\n\n[[File:Bogside (15), August 2009.JPG|thumb|left|[[Free Derry]] corner]]\nIn the late 1960s, armed loyalists attacked Catholic communities in response to the [[Northern Ireland civil rights movement]].{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=153}} To protect themselves, nationalists set up [[Citizen Defence Committees]] (not connected to [[physical force Irish republicanism|physical-force republican groups]]) which built and manned barricades and patrolled the neighborhood. In nationalist neighborhoods of [[Derry]] such as the [[Bogside]], [[Brandywell]], and [[Creggan, Derry|Creggan]], these committees worked to control petty crime by delivering stern lectures to offenders. In the 1970s, the [[Free Derry Police]] also operated independent of paramilitary groups. \"People's courts\" which mostly imposed sentences of [[community service]] based on a [[restorative justice]] approach operated in the early years of the conflict, but shut down due to police intimidation and because they did not have the authority of punishment imposed by paramilitaries.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=153}}{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=44\u201345}}{{sfn|Monaghan|2004|p=439}} In nationalist  Belfast, the [[Catholic Ex-Servicemen's Association]] initially played a role in keeping order.{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|pp=31\u201332}} At the same time, Protestant  neighbourhoods began to organize defence groups in response to retaliatory raids. Such groups formed the basis of the UDA.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=153}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002a|p=42}}\n\nThe [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) became the  major enforcer of informal justice in republican areas in the early 1970s, as the civil rights movement transitioned into guerilla war.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=44\u201345}} The RUC stopped entering West Belfast\u2014an economically deprived, overcrowded republican area\u2014in 1969, creating a \"[[no-go area]]\",{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=153}}{{sfn|McCorry|Morrissey|1989|p=283}} and many rural areas had a system of dual control between the IRA and the authorities.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=91}} At the same time, there was a spike in crime: from two murders and three or four armed robberies each year in the 1960s to 200 murders and 600 armed robberies annually during the next decade.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=89}} Despite making the news, rates of car theft were actually still lower in Northern Ireland than in England and Wales, although 70% of car thefts in Northern Ireland occurred in Belfast.{{sfn|McCorry|Morrissey|1989|pp=286\u2013287}} Petty criminals were often offered immunity by law enforcement in exchange for informing on paramilitaries.{{sfn|Munck|1984|pp=87, 91}} The origins of paramilitary vigilantism are not well documented,{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=7}} but sociologist [[Ronaldo Munck]] considers them to originate from \"community consciousness\".{{sfn|Munck|1984|pp=85\u201386}} During the first ten years of the Northern Ireland conflict, police did not enter republican areas.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=89}} During the 1975 truce, \"Provo Police Stations\" were set up by  [[Sinn F\u00e9in]],{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=45}} the political wing of the IRA.{{sfn|Stevenson|1996|p=125}} These centers shifted the responsibility of informal justice from the IRA to Sinn F\u00e9in. Once  a crime had been reported to Sinn F\u00e9in, the party would assign its Civil Administration Officers to  investigate. Suspects often were  given the opportunity to defend themselves to Sinn F\u00e9in before the organization made a decision on their guilt or innocence. Sinn F\u00e9in could issue a  warning or pass the information to the IRA for punishment.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=45\u201346}}\n\n==Causes==\nOne cause of vigilantism is the breakdown in law and order and lack of trust in the authorities.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=44, 52}}{{sfn|Jarman|2007|pp=3, 7}} According to anthropologist Neil Jarman, vigilantism emerged in both loyalist and republican areas due to the failings in state policing, a gap which paramilitaries ended up filling.{{sfn|Jarman|2007|pp=3, 7}} According to Munck, punishment attacks represent \"a sharp contest over the legitimacy of criminal justice within a society deeply divided along [[ethno-national]] lines\".{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=151}}  In republican neighbourhoods, the IRA was the only organization with the capability to offer an effective alternative to the British judicial system.{{sfn|Brooks|2019|p=211}}  The ideology of [[Sinn F\u00e9in (slogan)|self-reliance]] in defence from loyalist attacks came to extend to defending the community from crime, which created a cycle where the IRA was expected to deal with criminality but had no way to do so besides violent attacks.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|pp=362\u2013363}}{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=9}}{{efn|Some paramilitary groups do have the ability to hold prisoners captive for extended periods of time. However, this strains their resources so  much that it can only be used rarely.{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=131}}}}\n\n{{quotebox|align=right|width=25em|quote=The plain fact of the matter is if the North Belfast kneecapping squad stood for election tomorrow they would romp home on the first count. We are not a barbaric lot, we are just tired and frustrated, and disempowered by the joyriding and drug-loving crowd of lowlifes who make working class areas their happy hunting ground. |source=''[[Andersonstown News]]'', 18 March 2000{{sfn|Hamill|2002|p=62}}}}\n{{quotebox|align=right|width=25em|quote=We want to help people. And if you have to shoot someone to help people, then we\u2019ll do it... We know we are hurting people but we are hurting a parasite.|source=Dissident republican spokesperson in a 2018 [[BBC Three (online)|BBC Three]] documentary<ref name=\"BBC3\" />}}\nPopular demand for paramilitary punishment is widely regarded as one of the main causes of the attacks.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=156}} Both republican and loyalist paramilitaries claim that they began to enforce informal justice due to demand from their  communities,{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=44, 52}} and vigilantism came at the expense of the IRA's military campaign.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|p=362}}  Many locals believe the victims deserve the attacks, because they have typically broken local conventions governing acceptable behaviour and often actively seek out the circumstances that led to their punishment.{{sfn|Hamill|2002|p=68}}{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=66\u201367}}{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=9}} Some local republican and loyalist politicians have justified the attacks by saying that the official system fails working-class communities{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=9}} which bear the brunt of crime.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=92}} In community meetings attended by criminologist  Kieran McEvoy and sociologist Harry Mika around the turn of the century, the authors frequently encountered \"vocal support for punishment violence\" and accusations that local politicians who supported restorative justice were \"abandoning\" their responsibility to protect their communities.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=536}} \n\nUnlike law enforcement, which is bound by [[due process]], paramilitaries can act swiftly and directly in punishing offenders.{{sfn|Mallon ''et al.''|2019|p=2}}{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=362}} (Conviction rates for crimes such as burglary and joyriding are very low, due to the difficulty of securing evidence.{{sfn|Peyton|2002|p=s53}}) Because of the tight-knit nature of Northern Ireland communities, paramilitaries can often find the perpetrator via local gossip.{{sfn|Brewer ''et al.''|1998|pp=580\u2013581}} Local residents credit paramilitaries for keeping Belfast  relatively free of drugs<ref name=\"indy\" /> and non-political crime.{{sfn|Brewer ''et al.''|1998|p=581}} In 2019, ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' reported that PSNI still \"finds itself powerless in the face of influential paramilitaries\" to stop punishment attacks. In the words of a local resident, many people feel that \"at least somebody\u2019s doing something about [drug dealing]\".<ref name=\"Foreign Policy\" /> According to surveys, the number of Northern Ireland residents living in affected areas who think that punishment attacks are sometimes justified has decreased from 35% to 19% following the [[Department of Justice (Northern Ireland)|Department of Justice]]'s 2018 \"Ending the Harm\" campaign.<ref name=\"itimes\" />\n\nAfter the ceasefires declared by loyalist and republican paramilitaries in 1994, the number of shootings decreased while beatings increased as the groups wanted  to appear to be following the terms of the  ceasefire.{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|pp=42\u201343}} (In the months before the ceasefire, there had been a wave of shootings.{{sfn|Conway |1997|p=116}}) The overall rate of attacks spiked; one explanation for the rise in attacks was the decrease in conventional terrorism, which resulted in bored paramilitaries who turned their attention to punishment attacks.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=14}}  However, according to researcher Dermot Feenan there is no evidence for this.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=164}} After the peace agreement was finalized in 1998, the number of fatal terrorist attacks greatly decreased but beatings and intimidation continued to increase.{{sfn|Mallon ''et al.''|2019|p=1}} Within a few years shooting attacks  were also on the rise.{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|pp=42\u201343}}\n\nAccording to some writers, including [[Liam Kennedy (historian)|Liam Kennedy]] and [[Malachi O'Doherty]],{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=536}} protecting their  own communities is only a pretext and the paramilitaries' real goal is to consolidate control over the community.{{sfn|Morrison|2016|p=599}}{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|p=361}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=164}} Kennedy argues that paramilitaries are attempting to consolidate \"a patchwork of Mafia-style mini-states\" via vigilante violence and economically sustained by [[extortion]] and [[racketeering]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2001|loc=Trends over Time}}  Some have argued that paramilitary vigilantes only target drug dealers because they compete with paramilitary-sponsored organized crime.{{sfn|Brooks|2019|p=211}} However, researchers <!-- including Mika, McEvoy, Cavanaugh, and Frank Burton --> argue that \"the notion that paramilitaries can 'control' local communities is something of a myth\"{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=546}} which ignores the dependence of paramilitaries on their communities and the support for paramilitarism within those communities.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=546}}{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1997|p=49}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|pp=155, 164}}  Terrorism researcher [[Andrew Silke]] argues that both loyalist and republican paramilitaries are reluctant vigilantes, and that their vigilantism is unrelated to their {{lang|fr|raison d'\u00eatre}}. However, both informing and petty crime undermine the terrorist group, the latter because if the paramilitaries' response is not satisfactory, it can erode their local support.{{sfn|Silke|1998|pp=133\u2013134}}\n\n==Perpetrators==\n===Republican groups===\n[[File:Map of punishment attacks in Belfast, 1998\u20132000.png|thumb|Map of punishment attacks that occurred in Belfast between 1998 and 2000. North and East Belfast, as well as [[Shankill, Belfast|Shankill]], see the highest rate of loyalist punishment attacks, while West Belfast is the worst area for republican attacks.{{sfn|Knox|Dickson|2002|p=6}}]]\nThe [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA) targeted both \"political\" and \"normal\" criminals. The IRA defined \"political\" crime as informing or fraternizing with British soldiers, while \"normal\" crime was judged to include vandalism, theft, joyriding, rape, selling drugs, and \"[[antisocial behavior]]\"\u2014anything from verbally abusing the elderly to dumping rubbish.  \"Normal\" crimes by first-time offenders were often dealt with by a restorative justice approach based on providing restitution to victims. The typical punishment for repeat offenders  was [[kneecapping]],  a malicious wounding of the knee with a bullet.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=44\u201345}} The IRA claimed that its methods were more lenient than those of other insurgent groups, such as the [[National Liberation Front (Algeria)|Algerian FLN]] or the [[French resistance]], which Munck agrees with.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=86}}\n\nThe IRA also punished its own members for misusing the organization's name, losing weapons, disobeying orders, or breaking other rules, and launched purges against other republican paramilitary groups such as the Irish People's  Liberation Organisation and the Official IRA. Within the IRA, those responsible for punishment belonged to auxiliary cells and were considered the \"dregs\" of the organization.  The IRA maintained distinct sections for internal and external punishment.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=46\u201347}} Although informers were usually executed, part of the IRA's strategy for defeating informers included periodic amnesties (usually announced after murders) during which anyone could admit to informing without punishment.{{sfn|Sarma|2013|p=254}} Around 1980, the system of punishment attacks was questioned by IRA figures, which resulted in the increase in warnings given. The IRA pledged to stop kneecapping in 1983, and both shootings and beatings drastically declined. However, soon community members were calling for more paramilitary attacks to combat an increase in crime, especially violent rapes.{{sfn|Munck|1984|pp=89\u201390}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=157}}\n\nOther republican paramilitary groups also punished offenders but on a smaller scale.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=46\u201347}} [[Direct Action Against Drugs]] was an IRA [[front group]] that claimed responsibility for some murders of alleged drug dealers beginning in 1995, allowing the IRA to pretend to follow the ceasefire.{{sfn|Moran|2009|p=32}} DAAD drew up a list of alleged drug dealers and crossed their names off the list as they were executed.<ref name=\"independent\" /> Other republican anti-drug vigilante groups include [[Republican Action Against Drugs]],<ref name=\"btelegraph\" />{{sfn|Morrison|2016|p=607}} [[Irish Republican Movement]],<ref name=\"McClements\" />  and [[Action Against Drugs]].<ref name=\"BBC3\"/> Along with conventional terrorism, punishment attacks are a major feature of the [[dissident Irish republican campaign]] carried out by the [[New IRA]] and other groups.{{sfn|Morrison|2016|p=599}} However, the attacks are controversial among dissident republicans, who question whether any benefit of the attacks is worth the internal division and alienation of youth.{{sfn|Morrison|2016|p=608}}\n\n===Loyalist groups===\n{{see also|loyalist feud}}\n[[File:Shopping in Shankill, Belfast. - panoramio.jpg|thumb|left|Shankill Road is a hotspot for loyalist attacks]]\nUlster loyalist paramilitaries, whilst not drawing on historical precedents, justified their role in terms of maintaining order and enforcing the law. Unlike republican vigilantes, however, they saw their role as aiding the  [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]]  rather than subverting it. Nevertheless, they were prepared to mete out their own punishments in cases where they judged the  official justice system not to  deal harshly enough with the alleged offender. In 1971, the [[Ulster Defence Association]] (UDA), the largest Ulster loyalist group, formed as a merger between various neighbourhood watch and vigilante groups. It adopted the motto {{lang|la|Codenta Arma Togae}} (\"law before violence\") and states that its aim is to see order restored throughout Northern Ireland. The UDA has collected evidence on petty crime and used vigilante punishment against criminals, antisocial elements, rival Ulster loyalist paramilitary groups, and as a means of discipline within groups. It also used the  threat of punishment in order to  conscript new members.  The [[Ulster Volunteer Force]] (UVF) used to patrol the [[Shankill, Belfast|Shankill]] neighbourhood in Belfast. Criminals were warned or reported to the official police.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=49}}\n\nBetween 1973 and 1985, loyalists were responsible for many fewer punishment attacks than republicans, due to a view that their role was protecting Protestants from Catholics rather than enforcing rules within Protestant communities. From 1985 to 1998, they were responsible for a similar number of attacks. According to insider [[Sammy Duddy]], the UDA stopped reporting offenders to the police and started to engage in punishment shootings because the police was pressuring the offenders to inform on loyalist groups.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=134\u2013135}} Since the Good Friday Agreement, loyalists have committed significantly more punishment attacks than republicans.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=136}} The increase in punishment attacks has been attributed to increasing mistrust of official law enforcement, ineffectiveness at controlling petty crime, and perceived leniency of sentences.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=51}} Both the UDA and UVF have less internal discipline than the IRA,{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|p=364}}{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=136}} which means that an order to stop would be difficult to enforce. Loyalist groups' punishment style is more haphazard and groups who cannot find their intended target have been known to attack an innocent Catholic individual.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=136}} Individuals have joined loyalist paramilitaries to avoid a punishment attack from a rival group.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=50}}\n\nIn 1996, newspapers reported that the UVF had set up a \"court\" in Shankhill which fined  offenders for various offenses, but according to sociologist  Heather Hamill this is more likely a reflection of ability to pay rather than a genuine justice system  based on severity of the offence. In 2003, the North Belfast branch of the UDA announced that it was ceasing violent punishments in favour of \"naming and shaming\" offenders, who were forced to stand with placards announcing their offence. This change proved short lived.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=137}}\n\n==Attacks==\n===Overview===\nThe punishment methods of republican and loyalist paramilitaries are similar.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=50}} Because paramilitaries rely on popular support, they cannot overstep community consensus on appropriate punishment without risking the loss of support.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=86}} The penalty chosen would be based on the crime and potentially mitigating or aggravating factors such as criminal history, age, gender, and family background.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=46, 52}} Crime against targets valued by the community, such as religious leaders, pensioners, community centers, or locally owned businesses, tended to be punished more harshly than crimes against large corporations, which were frequently ignored.{{sfn|Brewer ''et al.''|1998|p=579}} Punishment attacks often begin when masked paramilitaries break into the victim's home.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=154}}  In other cases, victims would be told to show up at a certain time and place, either at a political front organization or at their home, for the attack.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=47}}{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=132}} Many victims keep these appointments because if they fail to do so, the punishment will be escalated in severity.{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=132}} These appointments are more likely to be made by republican than loyalist groups.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=50}} Some victims were able to negotiate the type of punishment.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=34, 69, 71}} In order to avoid the victims dying, paramilitaries frequently call emergency services after the attack.{{sfn|Peyton|2002|p=s54}} In  cases of mistaken identity, the IRA was known to issue apologies after the fact.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=47}}\n\nInitially, both republican and loyalist paramilitaries were reluctant to shoot or seriously harm women and children  younger than 16, although this became more frequent as the Troubles continued.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=46, 52}} Even female informers were usually subject to humiliation-type punishment rather than physical violence.{{sfn|Sarma|2013|p=252}}{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=46}} There were exceptions, such as the case of accused informer [[Jean McConville]], who was kidnapped and killed in 1972.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=46}}\n\n===Non-physical===\nMore minor punishments, often used on first offenders, are warnings, promises not to offend again, curfews, and fines.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=46}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=154}} Parents sometimes request that their child be warned in order to keep him or her from greater involvement in delinquency.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=69}} During the 1970s, when the IRA had the most control over established \"[[no-go area#Northern Ireland|no-go zones]]\",  humiliation was often used as a form of punishment. The victim was forced to hold a placard or [[tarred and feathered]]. In republican areas, women accused of fraternizing with British soldiers had their heads shaved. The use of such types of humiliation was greatest in the 1970s and decreased due to the risk of getting caught and complaints from [[Derry Women's Aid]] that the practice was misogynistic.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=46}}{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=76\u201377}}\n\nSometimes paramilitaries would approach a person and ask them to leave West Belfast{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=70\u201371}} or Northern Ireland within a certain period of time (such as 48 hours), with an implicit  threat of serious injury or execution if they did not comply.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=47}}{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=131}} It could be applied arbitrarily when paramilitaries go out looking for the victim but cannot find him, they will issue an expulsion order to friends or relatives.{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=132}} Expulsion was an alternative to violence favoured by paramilitaries because it removed the offender from the community whilst avoiding bloodshed.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=47}} However, victims frequently experienced it as the worst form of attack short of execution. Most victims are young, unemployed and lack educational qualifications as well as the skills and savings needed to establish themselves in a new area.{{sfn|Silke|1998|pp=124, 131}} Expulsion can be a life sentence but usually it lasts between three months and two years. Some victims, although they have not been convicted of any crime, go to juvenile detention centres to avoid punishment until their sentence expires.{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=132}}\n\n===Beatings===\n[[File:Weapons used against paramilitary punishment victims, 1997\u20132017.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Weapons used against paramilitary punishment victims who required orthopedic treatment, 1997\u20132017. GSW refers to [[gunshot wound]].]]\nSome individuals report that the attack was quite mild and no more than a \"cuff around the ear\" or being slapped around. Other beatings are more severe and the victim ends up in hospital for considerable period of time. Beatings are accomplished with instruments such as baseball bats, hammers, golf clubs, hurley sticks, iron bars,  concrete blocks, and cudgels (often studded with nails). The resulting injury can be quite  severe, involving flesh split by nails, broken skulls, broken limbs, punctured lungs, and other serious damage.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=72\u201373}}{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=47}}{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=11}} More injuries affected the limbs than the torso. In some cases, paramilitaries used powered drills and hacksaws to directly injure bone.{{sfn|Barr|Mollan|1989|p=740\u2013741}} Beatings became more severe after the 1994 ceasefires due to the reduction in shootings, and were often accomplished with baseball bats and similar implements studded with six-inch nails.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=11}} In the worst cases, individuals were hung from railings and nailed to fences in a form of [[crucifixion]].{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=9}} \n\n===Shootings===\n{{see also|Kneecapping}}\nVictims are typically shot in the knees,  ankles, thighs, elbows, ankles, or a combination of the above.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|p=360}} Kneecapping is considered a \"trademark\" of the IRA,{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=74}} although it became less popular over time because the disability and mortality incurred was unpopular with the community. It was replaced with low-velocity shots aimed at the soft tissue in the lower limbs. As a result, \"kneecapping\" is frequently a misnomer because by the 2010s most injuries targeted the [[femur]] or [[Popliteus muscle|popliteal]] area rather than the knee joint.{{sfn|McGarry ''et al.''|2017|p=93}}{{sfn|Peyton|2002|p=s54}}{{sfn|Lau ''et al.''|2017|p=747}} Typically, the victim is forced to lie face down and shot from behind.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=74}} Republican paramilitaries tended to shoot side to side while loyalists shot back to front, causing more severe damage.{{sfn|Peyton|2002|p=s54}} As with beatings, there are various degrees of shooting, with the number of shots, proximity to a joint, and the [[calibre]] of the firearm depending on the severity of the offence. If the victim is shot in the fleshy  part of the thigh, it will heal quickly with little damage. On the other hand, if they are shot directly in the joint it can cause permanent disability.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=47}}{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=74\u201375}}  An especially severe form is the \"six pack\", during which a victim is shot in both knees, elbows, and ankles.{{sfn|McGarry ''et al.''|2017|p=93}} Depending on the attack, shooting can leave relatively minor injuries compared to a severe beating,{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=12}}{{sfn|Knox|Dickson|2002|p=2}} with one NHS doctor estimating that 50% of those with such injuries will  have only minor scars.<ref name=\"Brutality\" /> The IRA sought the advice of doctors in how to cause serious but non-lethal injury. They were advised to shoot the ankles and wrists instead of the knees because it lessened the risk of the victim bleeding out, as happened to [[Murder of Andrew Kearney|Andrew Kearney]] in 1998.<ref name=\"doctors\" /> The harshest punishments are for informing, which typically results in execution.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|pp=45, 50}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|pp=163\u2013164}}\n\n===Consequences===\n[[File:Knee injury from punishment attack.png|thumb|left|Knee injury caused by a punishment shooting]]\nAccording to psychiatrist Oscar Daly, who treats victims of the attacks, the characteristics of those who tend to be victims\u2014such as poor parenting and preexisting mental health problems\u2014make them more vulnerable to psychological [[sequelae]]. A 1995 study found that symptoms of [[post-traumatic stress disorder]], such as [[Flashback (psychology)|flashbacks]], [[hypervigilance]], difficulty concentrating, and attempts to numb or minimize the incident, are common in youth who survive a punishment attack. According Hamill's research, desire to escape fear and the feeling of powerlessness can contribute to problems with alcoholism and  drug  abuse.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|pp=77\u201378}} More than one third of her subjects suffered from extended bouts of depression following attacks  and 22% said that they had attempted suicide.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=79}}{{sfn|Mallon ''et al.''|2019|p=2}} Mallon analyzed the 402 suicides in Northern Ireland between 2007 and 2009 and identified nineteen cases in which young men had killed themselves after being threatened with punishment attacks for alleged criminal or anti-social behaviour.{{sfn|Mallon ''et al.''|2019|p=4}}\n\nIn 2002, the [[National Health Service]] estimated that it spent at least \u00a31.5m annually on treating the victims of punishment attacks.<ref name=paramilitary-style/> Depending on the time period under consideration, the per-patient cost of treating victims who have been physically attacked varies from \u00a32,855 (2012\u20132013) to \u00a36,017 (pre-1994)  in 2015 pounds. These figures only include the first hospital admission and therefore do not include the cost of treating resulting psychological disorders. The lower cost is due both to less severe attacks and improved treatment techniques.{{sfn|McGarry ''et al.''|2017|p=92}} Many victims were treated at [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast]], which developed expertise in dealing with the particular injuries involved.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=90}}{{sfn|Barr|Mollan|1989|p=740\u2013741}} Punishment beatings often leave victims with serious injuries and permanently disabled.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=47}} Kneecapping often resulted in neurovascular damage which had to be treated with weeks in the hospital and extensive outpatient rehabilitation.{{sfn|Barr|Mollan|1989|p=740\u2013741}} However, medical advancements allowed most victims to regain most function in their limbs.{{sfn|Lau ''et al.''|2017|p=750}} Between 1969 and 2003, 13 patients treated at [[Musgrave Park Hospital]] in Belfast required leg amputation because of kneecapping attacks.{{sfn|Graham|Parke|2004|p=229}}\n\nIf considered \"innocent victims of violent crime\", victims of punishment attacks (like others injured by paramilitaries) are eligible for compensation by the [[Compensation Agency]] of the Northern Ireland Office.{{sfn|Knox|Dickson|2002|pp=10\u201311}}\n\n==Statistics==\n[[File:Punishment attacks in Northern Ireland, 1973\u20132008.png|frameless|right|upright=1.6]]\nPolice received reports  of 6,106 punishment attacks between 1973 and 2015, of which 3,113 incidents were attributed to loyalists and  2,993 to republicans.<ref name=\"rt\u00e9\" /> At least 115 people were killed by these attacks between 1973 and 2000.{{sfn|Silke|2000|loc=abstract}} There have been additional deaths since then, such as multiple murders claimed by Republican Action Against Drugs and the killing of Michael McGibbon in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Timeline of Irish dissident activity |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-10866072 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |work=BBC News |date=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC3\" /> These statistics only include incidents reported to the police, and are therefore an underestimate.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=51}} Pressure group [[Families Against Intimidation and Terror]] claims that it is a 30\u201350% underestimate,{{sfn|Knox|2002|pp=174, 176}} while according to Sharon Mallon, underreporting makes accurate measurement of these attacks impossible.{{sfn|Mallon|2017|p=3}} No statistics exist for other forms of penalties, such as expulsion,{{efn|Belfast victim-support group Base 2 knows of 453 people who were expelled between 1994 and 1996. Of these, 42% were expelled from Northern Ireland, 20% were ordered to leave their town, and 38% had to leave their neighbourhood only.{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=131}}}}  humiliation, fines, curfews, or warnings.{{sfn|Silke|1998|pp=123\u2013124}} The estimates of incidents in the 1970s is particularly suspect, since punishment beatings were not counted.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=14}} Almost half of all reported attacks have occurred since the Good Friday agreement.<ref name=\"PeaceInsight\" />\n\nMost victims of punishment attacks are young men or boys under 30 years of age.{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=137}} About one-quarter of victims are under the age of 20 and the youngest are thirteen years old.{{sfn|Knox|Dickson|2002|p=6}} Less than ten percent of victims are female.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=6}} Victims of loyalists are older on average; 33% are over the age of 30 years compared to 15% for republicans.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=7}} Since 1990, half of victims were attacked in Belfast.<ref name=\"rt\u00e9\" /> In most attacks, only one person is assaulted. Resistance is rarely attempted, because most victims perceive their situation to be hopeless. Sometimes, if a bystander steps in to defend the targeted person, they will be attacked as well.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|pp=6\u20138}} About three-quarters of attacks take place between 16:00 and midnight; the majority begin in the victim's residence (often they are abducted and taken elsewhere for the main attack).{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=9}} Most loyalist attacks involve between three and five attackers, but two-thirds of IRA attacks involve five or more attackers.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=10}} \n\nAfter a decrease in the early 2000s, punishment attacks are increasing again.{{sfn|Mallon ''et al.''|2019|p=2}}{{sfn|Topping|Byrne|2012|p=42}} In 2018, [[Community Restorative Justice Ireland]] estimated that each year there are 250-300 threats, significantly higher than the number reported to PSNI.<ref name=\"BBC3\" /> Between July 2018 and June 2019, 81 punishment attacks were reported to the police, on average more than one every four days.<ref name=\"itimes\" /> From January to November 2019, 68 attacks were reported.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Doherty |first1=Malachi |title=Thugs behind 'punishment' attacks act as if they enjoy some sort of community endorsement... shamefully, they're not wrong |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/opinion/columnists/malachi-odoherty/malachi-odoherty-thugs-behind-punishment-attacks-act-as-if-they-enjoy-some-sort-of-community-endorsement-shamefully-theyre-not-wrong-38735976.html |accessdate=30 November 2019 |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |date=28 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Victims==\n===\"Hoods\"===\nMost victims come from a delinquent youth subculture colloquially known as \"hoods\".{{sfn|Hamill|2011|p=98, ''passim''}}{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=8}}{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=91}} Offences that they commit range from organized drug dealing to joyriding.{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=91}} Hoods continue to offend even though they know that this puts them at high risk of punishment. According to research by Heather Hamill, this is because prestige in this subculture is based on [[Signalling theory|costly signals]] of toughness and individuals are able to attain even higher prestige when they show that they are undeterred by punishment attacks.{{sfn|Hamill|2002|pp=67\u201368}} According to Munck, hoods regard having been kneecapped as a \"mark of prestige\".{{sfn|Munck|1984|p=91}}\n\nDrug dealing is particularly strongly opposed by the IRA, with the commander of the Belfast Brigade declaring that drugs are the \"poison of our community\" and their purveyors responsible for \"CRIMES AGAINST HUMANITY\".{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|pp=165\u2013166}}\n\n===Politically motivated attacks===\nOther victims are attacked for political reasons, such as part of feuds with other groups. For example, in 1998 the IRA attacked both Kevin McQuillan, a leader in the rival [[Irish Republican Socialist Party]], and Michael Donnelly, chairman of [[Republican Sinn F\u00e9in]] in Derry.{{sfn|Silke|1998|p=134}} One reason for the resurgence of dissident republicans after the IRA's disbanding in 2005 was that previously, the organization  had been conducting campaigns of social ostracism, intimidation, kidnapping, and assassination against dissident republicans.{{sfn|Ross|2012|p=63}} These attacks deter opponents of paramilitary groups from criticizing them.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|pp=164\u2013165}}\n\nOther victims, such as Andrew Kearney and Andrew Peden, were attacked after quarreling with paramilitary members.{{sfn|Knox|Dickson |2002|pp= 6\u20137}}{{sfn|Monaghan|2004|p=441}}\n\n===Sexual offences===\nRepublican and loyalist paramilitaries both targeted gay men and individuals suspected of molesting children.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=166}}  Loyalist paramilitaries also deal harshly with sexual crimes. One Presbyterian minister, [[David J. Templeton]], was caught with homosexual pornography and died after a beating by the UVF in 1997.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=50}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Breen |first1=Suzanne |title=NI Presbyterian former minister dies of heart attack following beating |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ni-presbyterian-former-minister-dies-of-heart-attack-following-beating-1.55880 |accessdate=9 January 2020 |work=The Irish Times |language=en}}</ref> Republican paramilitaries shot a 79-year-old man in both arms and legs after mistaking him for an accused child molester.{{sfn|Knox|Dickson| 2002|p= 6}}\n\n==Opposition==\n===Campaigning===\nPunishment attacks are condemned by all major political parties in Northern Ireland<ref name=\"theyworkforyou\" />{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=9}} and by religious leaders.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dawson |first1=Greg |title=I was shot in the knee as a punishment |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-42014557 |accessdate=8 December 2019 |work=BBC News |date=20 November 2017}}</ref>  In 1990, Nancy Gracey set up the organization [[Families Against Intimidation and Terror]] to oppose punishment attacks after her grandson was killed in one.<ref name=\"independent\" /> Historian [[Liam Kennedy (historian)|Liam Kennedy]] has campaigned against the attacks, which he considers a form of [[child abuse]], considering that many victims are minors and some younger than 14.  Kennedy has accused Sinn F\u00e9in of involvement in  the attacks, which the party denies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kilpatrick |first1=Chris |title=A catalogue of brutality... by the thugs who shoot and beat children and then try to call it justice |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/a-catalogue-of-brutality-by-the-thugs-who-shoot-and-beat-children-and-then-try-to-call-it-justice-30734495.html |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |date=11 November 2014}}</ref> Beginning in the 1970s, the RUC conducted a propaganda campaign against punishment attacks, seeking to portray their perpetrators as preying on an innocent, harmonious community and seeking a \"monopoly on crime for themselves\".{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=166}} In 2018, the PSNI launched the \"Ending the Harm\" campaign to raise awareness of punishment attacks.<ref name=\"itimes\" />\n\n===Legality===\nExtrajudicial violence and threats are illegal in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Verkaik |first1=Robert |title=Police forces struggle to contain digital vigilante groups taking the law into their own hands |url=https://inews.co.uk/news/uk/digital-vigilante-groups-justice-541103 |accessdate=26 November 2019 |work=[[iNews]] |date=3 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref> People  who carry out punishment attacks can be prosecuted for crimes such as [[assault]], [[battery (crime)|battery]], and [[Assault occasioning actual bodily harm|bodily harm]].{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|p=43}} The sixth of the [[Mitchell Principles]], which paramilitary groups agreed to abide by in 1998, explicitly  forbids extrajudicial punishment and requires that signatories put an end to the practice.{{sfn|Monaghan|2002|p=48}}   The United States was reluctant to threaten the success of the peace process due to punishment attacks, because it considered that these did not fit the conventional definition of terrorism.{{sfn|Stevenson|1996|pp=134\u2013135}} As a result, the victims of punishment attacks became \"expendable and legitimate targets for violence\".{{sfn|Knox|2001|p=196}} However, it was \"intolerably awkward ... to turn a blind eye to vigilante murder\".{{sfn|Stevenson|1996|p=135}} The ban on punishment attacks was never well enforced, and paramilitaries make a distinction between \"punishment\" and military actions, only ceasing the latter. Loyalist paramilitaries UDA, UFF, and LVF were re-[[List of designated terrorist groups|listed as terrorist organizations]]  in October 2001 after they were found to be involved in punishment attacks.{{sfn|Knox|Monaghan|2002|pp=42\u201343}}\n\nThe authorities have been unable or unwilling to prosecute the perpetrators of the attacks, because attackers usually wear masks and even if aware of their identity, many victims are reluctant to identify them for fear of retaliation.{{sfn|Peyton|2002|p=s54}}{{sfn|Cody|2008|p=12}}  Of 317 punishment attacks reported to the PSNI between 2013 and 2017, only 10 cases resulted in charges or a court summons.<ref name=\"prosecution\" /> According to research by Andrew Silke and Max Taylor on punishment attacks between July 1994 and December 1996, loyalists were convicted at a four times higher rate than republican attackers for their participation in attacks. This was because working-class Protestants were more likely to cooperate with the police.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|pp=12\u201313}} In a plurality of cases analyzed by Silke and Taylor, there are no witnesses besides the victim.{{sfn|Silke|Taylor|2002|p=10}} PSNI established the [[Paramilitary Crime Task Force]] in 2017, in part to crack down on punishment attacks.<ref name=\"BBC3\" /><ref name=\"taskforce\" />\n\nAccording to [[Human Rights Watch]], [[Geneva Conventions#Common Article 3 relating to non-international armed conflict|Common Article 3]] of the [[1949 Geneva Convention]], which lays down rules for internal armed conflicts, applies to the Northern Ireland conflict.{{sfn|Human Rights Watch|1997|loc=5. Paramilitary \"Policing\": Requirements of International Law}} Punishment attacks constitute [[torture]],{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=154}} \"violate the [[right to life]], freedom from humiliating and degrading treatment, the right to due process and the [[right to a fair trial|guarantee of a fair trial]]\".{{sfn|Human Rights Watch|1997|loc=5. Paramilitary \"Policing\": Requirements of International Law}}\n\n===Restorative justice===\nIn 1990, the Belfast-based victim support group Base 2 was founded. In the first eight years, it helped more than 1,000 people stay in their communities and avoid punishment attacks.{{sfn|Conway |1997|pp=109-110}} Since then, there have been community-based attempts to mediate conflict between paramilitaries and their targets via a restorative justice approach. These interventions have included verifying if an individual is under sentence of expulsion, helping such individuals relocate elsewhere, and eventually reintegrating them into the community.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|p=368}} Alleged offenders may be offered mediation with the wronged party and asked to offer restitution or perform community service. As part of the programme, they have to stop the behaviour and cease using alcohol and drugs. These are voluntary programmes, and require the agreement of both parties. Some offenders prefer the official justice system or to suffer paramilitary punishment.{{sfn|Jarman|2007|pp=11-12}}\n\nSinn F\u00e9in supported restorative justice, which was endorsed by the IRA in 1999; the organization also asked locals to stop requesting punishment attacks.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|p=369}} About this time, Community Restorative Justice Ireland (CRJI) was established to coordinate restorative justice initiatives in republican areas.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=537}}{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=167}} The RUC's opposition to the centres made them ideologically acceptable to republicans.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2001|p=369}} Before 2007, the republican restorative justice centres did not cooperate with the PSNI.{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=12}} CRJI is opposed by dissident republicans; ''[[Saoirse Irish Freedom]]'' (the organ of Republican Sinn F\u00e9in) once described it as \"British [[double speak]] for collaboration with Crown Forces\".{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=554}} Loyalist neighbourhoods have also seen community restorative justice approaches, organized by [[Northern Ireland Alternatives]],<ref name=\"PeaceInsight\" /> which originated in the greater Shankill area{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=167}} and worked closely with the police from the beginning,{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=12}} despite scepticism from law enforcement.{{sfn|Feenan|2002b|p=167}}\n\nProponents of restorative justice argue that they are the only way to end paramilitary violence and are a legitimate form of [[legal pluralism]].<ref name=\"PeaceInsight\" />{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=13}} According to a study by [[Atlantic Philanthropies]], Alternatives prevented 71% of punishment attacks by loyalists and CRJI prevented 81% of attacks by republicans.{{sfn|Cody|2008|p=556}} Critics argue that the restorative justice approach legitimizes the role of paramilitaries in informal justice and allows them to retain the threat of violent attacks if they are not satisfied with the result.<ref name=\"PeaceInsight\" />{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=13}} In 2006, the eighth report of the International Monitoring Commission described participation in  restorative justice as one means by which paramilitaries attempted to maintain their role and exert influence.{{sfn|Jarman|2007|p=10}} Another argument against restorative justice is that it institutionalizes a different justice system for the rich and poor.{{sfn|McEvoy|Mika|2002|p=552}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|25em|refs=\n<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news |last1=Higgins |first1=Erica Doyle |title=The UVF, UDA, PIRA and the INLA: Paramilitary groups of Northern Ireland explained |url=https://www.irishpost.com/news/uvf-uda-pira-and-the-inla-the-paramilitary-groups-explained-96968 |accessdate=27 November 2019 |work=[[The Irish Post]] |date=8 August 2016}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times\">{{cite news |title=Activities and structure