 |isbn=978-0-85389-615-9 |pages=145\u2013167 |language=en |chapter=Alternative Justice in Ireland}}\n*{{cite conference |last1=Kennedy |first1=Liam |authorlink=Liam  Kennedy (historian)|title=Nightmares within Nightmares: Paramilitary Repression within Working Class Communities|conference=Crime and Punishment in West Belfast |date=1995 |publisher=Summer School |location=Belfast |isbn=978-0-85389-588-6 |language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Munck |first1=Ronaldo|authorlink=Ronaldo Munck |editor1-last=Tomlinson |editor1-first=Mike |editor2-last=McCullagh |editor2-first=Ciaran |editor3-last=Varley |editor3-first=Tony |title=Whose Law and Order? Aspects of Crime and Social Control in Irish Society |date=1988 |publisher=Sociological Association of Ireland : Distributed by Queen's University Bookshop Ltd. |isbn=978-0-9513411-0-0 |language=English |chapter=The Lads and the Hoods: Alternative Justice in an Irish Context}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.endingtheharm.com/ Ending the Harm], official campaign against punishment attacks\n*[https://batchgeo.com/map/6735208584128eb7fde05b0558020159 Interactive map of punishment attacks] 1990\u20132014, by [[RT\u00c9]]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/p06jy0dl/stacey-dooley-investigates-shot-by-my-neighbour 2018 BBC documentary on punishment attacks], by [[Stacey Dooley]] \n{{the Troubles}}\n\n[[Category:The Troubles (Northern Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Vigilantism]]\n[[Category:Crime in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Paramilitary punishment attacks in Northern Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Eisfbnore", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLoyalist groups:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paramilitary_punishment_attacks_in_Northern_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "Ynes Mexia", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican-American botanist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Yn\u00e9s Enriquetta Julietta Mex\u00eda\n| image             = Ynes_Mexia.jpg\n| birth_date        = May 24, 1870\n| birth_place       = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|1938|7|12|1870|5|24}}\n| death_place       = [[Berkeley, California]], United States\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = United States<br />Mexico\n| nationality       = [[Mexicans|Mexican]], [[American]]\n| ethnicity         = \n| field             = [[Botany]]\n| work_institutions = \n| alma_mater        = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| prizes            = \n| religion          = \n| native_name       = Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda\n| alt               = Woman standing in front of plants, wearing a long coat and glasses\n| awards            = Life member of the [[California Academy of Sciences]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = Mexia\n}}\n\n'''Yn\u00e9s Enriquetta Julietta Mex\u00eda''' (May 24, 1870 \u2013 July 12, 1938) was a [[Mexican Americans|Mexican-American]] botanist known for her collection of novel plant specimens from areas of [[Mexico]], [[Peru]], and [[Colombia]]. She discovered a new genus of ''[[Asteraceae]]'' and was the most accomplished plant collector of her time. Botanist and explorer Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda, braved earthquakes, bogs, and poisonous berries all for the sake of botanical discoveries.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://canadajournal.net/world/ynes-mexia-google-doodle-honors-tenacious-mexican-american-and-explorer-59595-2019/|title=Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda: Google Doodle Honors tenacious Mexican-American and explorer|last=News|date=2019-09-15|website=Canada Journal - News of the World|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nYn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda was born in 1870 in Washington, D.C. to Enrique Mex\u00eda and Sarah Wilmer Mex\u00eda.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf|title=Research Archive Cal Academy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She was the daughter of a Mexican diplomat and the granddaughter of a Mexican general. When she was very young, her parents divorced. Her father returned to Mexico, and her mother moved the family to Texas. Mex\u00eda later moved to Mexico.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybg.org/blogs/science-talk/2015/02/late-bloomer-the-short-prolific-career-of-ynes-mexia/|title=Late Bloomer: The Short, Prolific Career of Ynes Mexia|date=2015-02-26|website=Science Talk Archive|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> \n\n{{Citation needed span|text=In 1909, in her late thirties, she suffered a mental and physical breakdown that spurred her to move to San Francisco and seek medical care.|date=March 2020|reason=}} Her second husband continued to live in Mexico, and they eventually separated. There she started going on excursions into the mountains of Northern California with the [[Sierra Club]] and fell in love with the redwoods, the birds, the plants, and the quiet. <ref name=\":4\" /> She became involved in social work and was an active member of the [[Sierra Club]], which motivated her to attend the University of California, Berkeley.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nHer interest in botanical collecting began in 1922 when she joined an expedition led by [[Eustace L. Furlong|Eustace. L. Furlong]], a Berkeley paleontologist. She then enrolled in a course on flowering plants at the [[Hopkins Marine Station]] with [[LeRoy Abrams]] in Pacific Grove, California.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucjepsarchives.berkeley.edu/archon/?p=collections/findingaid&id=77&q=&rootcontentid=7350|title=Ynes Mexia collection, 1918-1966 {{!}} University and Jepson Herbaria Archives, University of California, Berkeley|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A 1980 letter from [[John Thomas Howell]] reminisces about the autumn of 1923:<blockquote>\"When I was enrolled in freshman botany at UCB and Mrs. Mex\u00eda was attending advanced classes... We were on a field trip with the Calypso Club, the student botanical club. We had spent the day under the guidance of Herbert Mason (then a graduate student under Prof. Jepson) exploring the floristic riches of Jasper Ridge... Separated from the rest of the club, we made a wrong turn...reached the station long after our train had departed... Eventually we arrived in Berkeley (by train to San Francisco, streetcar to Ferry Building, ferry across the Bay, interurban to Berkeley, streetcar to our homes). Mrs. Mex\u00eda never let me forget it!\" </blockquote>At that time, it was very remarkable for that experience to have occurred unchaperoned.<ref name=\":6\" /> In 1924 she became a United States citizen.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://latinonaturalhistory.biodiversityexhibition.com/en/card/ynes-mexia|title=Ynes Mexia {{!}} Latino Natural History|website=latinonaturalhistory.biodiversityexhibition.com|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> \n\nIn July of 1925, at the age of 55, Yn\u00e9s wrote to [[Alice Eastwood]], letting Eastwood know that she was about to accompany Stanford's Assistant Herbarium Curator, [[Roxana Stinchfield Ferris|Roxanna Ferris]], on a collecting trip to Mexico. This would be her first botanical exploration trip to Mexico. Once in Mexico, Mex\u00eda decided that she could accomplish more on her own and abandoned the group, traveling the country for two years and collecting more than 1,500 specimens.<ref name=\":5\" /> The trip resulted in 500 species being collected, including one named in Mex\u00eda's honor, ''Mimosa mexiae''. Finally, in middle age, Mex\u00eda had found her purpose in life, writing: \"\u2026 I have a job, [where] I produce something real and lasting.\"<ref name=\":7\" /> She made three additional expeditions to Mexico and collected throughout South America in remote areas of [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]], [[Ecuador]], and [[Peru]]. She also collected in [[Alaska]] and other areas of the continental United States.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nAfter her first major expedition to [[Sinaloa|Sinaloa, Mexico]] in 1925, she spent 13 years traveling from Alaska to [[Tierra del Fuego]], often shocking those she met because she was traveling solo, riding horseback with knickers, and preferring to sleep outside even when a bed was available. \"A well-known collector and explorer stated very positively that 'it was impossible for a woman to travel alone in Latin America,'\" she wrote, continuing, \"I decided that if I wanted to become better acquainted with the South American continent the best way would be to make my way right across it.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1938, during an expedition to [[Oaxaca]], Mexico, Mex\u00eda became ill. She tried to continue but had to turn back and return to the United States, where she was diagnosed with lung cancer. She died within one month at age 68. [[William Edward Colby|William E. Colby]], the secretary of the Sierra Club, wrote, \"All who knew Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda could not fail to be impressed by her friendly unassuming spirit, and by that rare courage which enabled her to travel, much of the time alone, in lands where few would dare to follow.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/2390204/ynes-mexia-plant-collector|title=This Trailblazing Plant Collector Found Solace in Nature|last=Siber|first=Kate|date=2019-02-20|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn the same 1980 letter where he described his student botanical club adventure with Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda, [[John Thomas Howell]] refers to her as a \"close friend of Alice Eastwood.\" He continues, \"In 1933 she accompanied Miss Eastwood and me on the first Eastwood and Howell collecting expedition.\u2026.in an open Model T Ford, that traversed parts of Nevada, Utah, Arizona, and California...and netted over 1300 collection numbers... Mrs. Mex\u00eda was to me a dear good friend.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Career ==\nOnce, Mex\u00eda joined a collecting trip to Mexico where she fell off a cliff, injuring her hand and fracturing her ribs.<ref name=\":7\" /> No obstacle could stand in Mex\u00eda's way, whether that be broken bones, poison, or dangerous terrain. She was an adventurer in the name of science. In 1928 she was hired to collect plants in Alaska. The next year she went to South America and travelled by canoe down the Amazon River, covering 4,800 kilometres in two and a half years to its source in the Andes.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000033443|title=Mexia, Ynes Enriquetta Julietta (1870-1938) on JSTOR|website=plants.jstor.org|doi=10.1093/anb/9780198606697.article.1302002|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> Her specimens were widely distributed to herbaria throughout the United States and western Europe. In addition to collecting, Mex\u00eda wrote articles and gave lectures describing her adventures and travels.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nDuring her collecting trips, Mex\u00eda would occasionally join other expeditions, including one headed by [[A. S. Hitchcock|A.S. Hitchcock]] and [[Mary Agnes Chase|Agnes Chase]] of the [[United States National Herbarium|U.S. National Herbarium]], and [[Thomas Harper Goodspeed|T. Harper Goodspeed]]'s University of California Botanical Expedition. Mex\u00eda learned how to collect from Alice Eastwood of the [[California Academy of Sciences]]. [[Nina Floy Bracelin]] served as Mex\u00eda's collection manager, caring for the specimens and sending them out for identification.<ref name=\":7\" /> Credit is due to Bracelin, affectionately known as \"Bracie,\" who prepared Mex\u00eda's specimens for herbaria. She worked diligently to label the specimens, sending sets to specialists so their species could be determined and distributing the duplicates. Mex\u00eda was said to be more interested in exploration and discovery rather than preparing her specimens, but her legacy lives on through those preserved botanical collections.<ref name=\":5\" /> In her will, Mex\u00eda left enough money to the California Academy of Sciences to hire Bracelin as an assistant to Alice Eastwood.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nMex\u00eda was an active member of many scientific societies, including the [[California Botanical Society]], the [[Sierra Club]], the Audubon Association of the Pacific, the Sociedad Geogr\u00e1fica de Lima, and the California Academy of Sciences. She was also an honorary member of the Departamento Forestal, de Caza y Pesca de Mexico. Her specimens can be viewed at the California Academy of Sciences (main collection), the [[Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia]], the [[Field Museum of Natural History]], the [[Harvard University Herbaria|Gray Herbarium]], the [[New York Botanical Garden]], the [[United States National Herbarium|Smithsonian Institution]], the [[University of California, Berkeley]], and the [[United States National Arboretum|U.S. National Arboretum]], as well as several museums and botanical gardens throughout Europe. Her personal papers are preserved at the California Academy of Sciences and at the [[Bancroft Library]] at the University of California, Berkeley.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Accomplishments ==\nMex\u00eda was also unusual for an American botanical collector during that era. Not only was she a woman, she was also of Mexican heritage and suffered some prejudice in a largely white field, and she was older\u2014she started her career in her mid-fifties. \"Women were actively dissuaded from doing that kind of work, because it was considered unfeminine and dangerous,\" says Vassiliki Betty Smocovitis, a professor of the history of biological sciences at the University of Florida. \"You actually have to camp out, you couldn\u2019t wash your hair, you were living a kind of rough life, and that could be dangerous\u2026. But Mex\u00eda had agency. She was doing exactly the work that she wanted to do.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Mex\u00eda had a life membership in the California Academy of Sciences and published a book, ''Brazilian Ferns Collected by Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda'', with [[Edwin Copeland|Edwin Bingham Copeland]], in 1932.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brazillian Ferns Collected by Ynes Mexia|last=Mexia|first=Ynes|publisher=The University of California Press|year=1932|isbn=|location=Berkeley|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThough Mex\u00eda had a short professional career\u2014only 13 years\u2014compared to many other academics, she collected a huge number of plant specimens. According to the British Natural History museum, she collected at least 145,000 plant specimens during her travels,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000033443|title=Mexia, Ynes Enriquetta Julietta (1870-1938) on JSTOR|last=|first=|date=|website=plants.jstor.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> 500 of which were new species.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://ucjepsarchives.berkeley.edu/archon/?p=collections/findingaid&id=77&q=&rootcontentid=7350|title=Ynes Mexia collection, 1918-1966|last=|first=|date=|website=University and Jepson Herbaria Archives, [[University of California, Berkeley]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> During her first expedition, she collected 500 specimens, which is the same number collected during Darwin's voyage on the Beagle.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://massivesci.com/articles/ynes-mexia-our-heroes/|title=Meet Ynes Mexia, late-blooming botanist whose adventures rivaled Darwin\u2019s|last=Serrato Marks|first=Gabriela|date=|website=massivesci.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> Although curators are still working to catalogue her full selection of specimens, 50 new species have already been named after her.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n<br /> \n<references />{{Copyvio/core\n|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2014/8/2/1302842/-Women-in-Science-Ynes-Mexia-1870-1938 http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54\n|month = September\n|day = 16\n|year = 2019\n|time = 23:22\n|timestamp = 20190916232247}}\n<!-- Do not use the \"Copyvio/core\" template directly; the above line is generated by {{subst:Copyvio}} -->\nYn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda was born in [[Washington, D.C.]] on May 24, 1870, to her Mexican diplomat father, [[Enrique Mex\u00eda]] (son of Mexican general [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Mex\u00eda]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921191022/https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54 |archive-date=2018-09-21 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>), and Sarah Wilmer. The marriage broke up in 1873, when Yn\u00e9s was three years old, and her father went back to Mexico City. Her mother took the children, including Yn\u00e9s and six others from a previous marriage,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2014/8/2/1302842/-Women-in-Science-Ynes-Mexia-1870-1938|title=Women in Science: Ynes Mexia 1870\u20131938|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> and moved the area of present-day [[Mexia, Texas]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf|title=Ynes Mexia (1870\u20131938) Biographical Sketch by Jane Radcliffe, Archives Volunteer|last=Radcliffe|first=Jane|date=June 23, 2011|website=Ynes Mexia (1870\u20131938) Biographical Sketch by Jane Radcliffe, Archives Volunteer|publisher=California Academy of Sciences|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54|title=Mexia de Reygades, Ynes|last=Garc\u00eda|first=Mar\u00eda-Cristina Garc\u00eda|date=June 15, 2010|website=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMex\u00eda spent most of her childhood in Texas and received her secondary education in private schools in Philadelphia and Ontario, Canada.<ref name=\":2\" /> She attended Saint Joseph's Academy in [[Emmitsburg, Maryland]]; after she finished there, she moved to [[Mexico City]], where she lived at the family [[hacienda]] for 10 years and took care of her father, who died in 1896.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|McLoone|1997|pp=23\u201330}} She planned to become a nun, but her father's will stipulated that if she did, she would be cut out of the inheritance she shared with a stepsister. She and her stepsister fought over the money with her father's mistress and a stepbrother.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe married Herman de Laue, a Spanish-German merchant, in 1897, but the brief marriage ended upon his death in 1904.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}} Her second marriage, to D. Augustin Reygados, 16 years her junior, was also short-lived. He badly mismanaged her poultry business while she received medical treatment in San Francisco, leading her to divorce him in 1908.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}<ref name=\":0\" /> After her marriage to Reygados ended, she began a career as a [[social worker]] in [[San Francisco]]. In 1921, she matriculated at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], motivated by trips with the [[Sierra Club]], where a [[botany]] class sparked her interest in the field; however, she never received a degree.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Bailey|1994|pp=248\u201349}} She died in Berkeley on July 12, 1938, from [[lung cancer]] after falling ill on a collecting trip to Mexico.{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career and legacy==\n<!-- Please do not remove or change this Copyvio message until the issue is settled -->\n{{Nobots}}\n{{Copyvio/core\n|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2014/8/2/1302842/-Women-in-Science-Ynes-Mexia-1870-1938 http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54\n|month = September\n|day = 16\n|year = 2019\n|time = 23:23\n|timestamp = 20190916232311}}\n<!-- Do not use the \"Copyvio/core\" template directly; the above line is generated by {{subst:Copyvio}} -->\nMex\u00eda began her botany career at the age of 55 with a 1925 trip to western [[Mexico]] under the tutelage of [[Roxana Stinchfield Ferris|Roxanna Ferris]], a botanist at [[Stanford University]]. Mex\u00eda fell off a cliff and was injured, halting the trip, which yielded 500 specimens, including several new species. The first species to be named after her, ''[[Mimosa mexiae]]'', was discovered on this excursion.{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}}\n\nOver the next 13 years, she traveled to [[Argentina]], [[Chile]], [[Denali]] (in 1928), [[Brazil]] (in 1929), [[Ecuador]] (in 1934), [[Peru]] and the Straits of Magellan (in 1935), and southwestern Mexico (in 1937) on seven different collecting trips, discovering one new genus, ''[[Mexianthus]]'', and many new species among her 150,000 total specimens.{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}}{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}} She frequently traveled alone, which was rare for women in the early 20th century.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://massivesci.com/articles/ynes-mexia-our-heroes/|title=Meet Ynes Mexia, late-blooming botanist whose adventures rivaled Darwin\u2019s|last=Serrato Marks|first=Gabriela|date=2019-05-03|website=[[Massive Science]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> During her trip to Western Mexico, she collected over 33,000 specimens,{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}} including 50 new species.{{sfn|Oakes|2002|pp=252\u201353}} In Ecuador, Mex\u00eda worked with the Bureau of Plant Industry and Exploration, part of Ecuador's Department of Agriculture.{{sfn|Mongillo|2001|pp=179\u201380}} There, she looked for the wax palm, [[cinchona]], and herbs that bind to the soil.{{sfn|Mongillo|2001|pp=179\u201380}} Mex\u00eda once traveled up the [[Amazon River]] to its source in the Andes mountains with a guide and three other men in a canoe.{{sfn|McLoone|1997|pp=23\u201330}} She also spent three months living with the [[Aguaruna people| Araguarunas]],{{efn-ua|\"Aguaruna\" and \"Araguaruna\" seem to be used interchangeably in the botanical and ethnographic literatures. E.g., from the bibliography of [https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF02864549 Folk taxonomy and evolutionary dynamics of cassava: A case study in Ubatuba, Brazil] (underlining added):\n* BOSTER, J.S. Classification, cultivation, and selection of {{uu|Araguaruna}} cultivars of ''Manihot esculenta'' (Euphorbiaceae). '''Advances in Economic Botany''', v.1, p.34-47, 1984.\n* BOSTER, J.S. Selection for perceptual distinctiveness: evidence from {{uu|Aguaruna}} cultivars of ''Manihot esculenta''. '''Economic Botany''', v.39, n.3, p.310-325, 1985.}} \na native group in the Amazon.{{sfn|McLoone|1997|pp=23\u201330}} All of these excursions were funded by the sale of her specimens to collectors and institutions alike.{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}} Specimens from these trips were stored in the [[Gray Herbarium]] at [[Harvard University]] and the [[Field Museum of Natural History]] in [[Chicago]].{{sfn|Bailey|1994|pp=248\u201349}}\n\nShe often lectured in the San Francisco [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]], sharing stories and photographs of her travels.<ref name=\":2\" /> Notes on her expeditions appeared regularly in ''The Gull'', the newsletter of the Audubon Society of the Pacific, between 1926 and 1935.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The ''[http://vault.sierraclub.org/history/bulletin/ Sierra Club Bulletin]'' published two accounts of her adventures, \"Three Thousand Miles up the Amazon\" (SCB, 18:1 [1933], 88\u201396),<ref name=\"vault.sierraclub.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://vault.sierraclub.org/history/bulletin/#M|title=Sierra Club Bulletin  \u2013 History |publisher= Sierra Club|website=vault.sierraclub.org|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> and \"Camping on the Equator\" (SCB, 22:1 [1937], 85\u201391).<ref name=\"vault.sierraclub.org\"/> Several accounts of her expeditions were published in ''[http://calbotsoc.org/madrono/ Madrono]'', the journal of the [[California Botanical Society]]. It also published a biographical note after her death in 1938 (''Madrono'', October, 1938, Vol. IV, No. 8, 274\u201375).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calbotsoc.org/80-year-index/|title=California Botanical Society|last=Society|first=California Botanical|website=calbotsoc.org|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> She was a member of the [[California Botanical Society]], the [[Sierra Club]], the Audubon Association of the Pacific, the [http://www.socgeolima.org.pe/ Sociedad Geografica de Lima, Peru], and had been made a life member of the [[California Academy of Sciences]]. She was also an honorary member of the Departamento Forestal y de Casa y Pesca de Mexico.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMex\u00eda was remembered by her colleagues for her expertise on life in the field and her resilience in the tough conditions,{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}} as well as her impulsiveness and fractious but generous personality.{{sfn|Bailey|1994|pp=248\u201349}} They lauded her meticulous, careful work and her skills as a collector.{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}\n\nThere is substantial agreement that Mex\u00eda collected some 150,000 specimens in her lifetime.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Women in the Field: America's Pioneer Naturalists.|last=Bonta|first=Marcia Myers|authorlink=Marcia Bonta|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|year=1991|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Estimates of new species range from two to 500.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [http://vault.sierraclub.org/history/bulletin/ Sierra Club Bulletin] credits her with two new genera.<ref name=\":1\" /> ''[[Mexianthus]]'', named for Mex\u00eda, is a genus of [[Asteraceae]].{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}\n\nHer specimen collections can be viewed at the California Academy of Sciences.<ref name=\":1\" /> Portions are duplicated at the [[Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University|Academy of Natural Sciences]], Philadelphia; [[Catholic University of America|Catholic University, Washington, D.C.]]; [[Field Museum of Natural History|the Field Museum of Natural History, Chicago]]; [[Harvard University Herbaria|Gray Herbarium]], Harvard University; the [[University of California, Berkeley|University of California]], Berkeley; and important museums and botanical gardens in London, Copenhagen, Geneva, Paris, Stockholm, and Zurich. Her personal papers are at the California Academy of Sciences and at the [[Bancroft Library]] at UC Berkeley.\n\n===Google Doodle===\n\nMex\u00eda's legacy was recognized in the [[Google Doodle]] for September 15, 2019.\n<br />\n{{Botanist|Mexia}}\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n* [[List of botanists|Botanists]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Notelist-ua}}\n;Citations\n{{reflist}}\n\n;References\n* {{citation\n  | title = American Women in Science\n  | last = Bailey\n  | first = Martha J.\n  | year = 1994\n  | publisher = ABC-CLIO\n  | isbn = 0-87436-740-9\n  | url = khttps://archive.org/details/americanwomenins00bail_0\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Women Explorers in North and South America\n  | last = McLoone\n  | first = Margo\n  | year = 1997\n  | publisher = Capstone\n  | isbn = 978-1560655077\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Environmental Activists\n  | last = Mongilloo\n  | first = John\n  | year = 2001\n  | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group\n  | isbn = 0313308845\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/environmentalact0000unse\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = International Encyclopedia of Women Scientists\n  | last = Oakes\n  | first = Elizabeth H.\n  | publisher = Facts On File, Inc.,\n  | year = 2002\n  | isbn = 0-8160-4381-7\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/internationalenc00oake\n  }}\n* {{citation@\n  | title = Ynes Mexia\n  | last1 = Ogilvie\n  | first1 = Marilyn\n  | last2 = Harvey\n  | first2 = Joy\n  | work = The Biographical Dictionary of Women in Science\n  | year = 2000\n  | isbn = 0-415-92038-8\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/biographicaldict00ogil_0\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | last = Petrusso\n  | first = Annette\n  | title = Ynes Mexia\n  | work = Notable Women Scientists\n  | editor-last = Proffitt\n  | editor-first = Pamela\n  | year = 1999\n  | publisher = Gale Group Inc.\n  | isbn = 0-7876-3900-1\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/notablewomenscie00pame\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = A Biographical Dictionary A to Z of Women in Science and Math\n  | last = Yount\n  | first = Lisa\n  | publisher = Facts on File Inc.\n  | year = 1999\n  | isbn = 0-8160-3797-3\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/tozofwomeninscie00youn\n  }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Ynes Mexia |sopt=t}}\n* [http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf8f59n9vd/ Guide to the Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda Papers] at [[The Bancroft Library]]\n* [http://thememorypalace.us/2017/03/roots-and-branches-and-wind-bourne-seeds/ The Memory Palace Episode 107: Roots and Branches and Wind-Borne Seeds]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mexia, Ynes}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1938 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women botanists]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from lung cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Mexican women scientists]]\n[[Category:American women botanists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:American people of Mexican descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American botanists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican-American botanist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Yn\u00e9s Enriquetta Julietta Mex\u00eda\n| image             = Ynes_Mexia.jpg\n| birth_date        = May 24, 1870\n| birth_place       = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|1938|7|12|1870|5|24}}\n| death_place       = [[Berkeley, California]], United States\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = United States<br />Mexico\n| nationality       = [[Mexican]], [[American]]\n| ethnicity         = \n| field             = [[Botany]]\n| work_institutions = \n| alma_mater        = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| prizes            = \n| religion          = \n| native_name       = Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda\n| alt               = Woman standing in front of plants, wearing a long coat and glasses\n| awards            = Life member of the [[California Academy of Sciences]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = Mexia\n}}\n\n'''Yn\u00e9s Enriquetta Julietta Mex\u00eda''' (May 24, 1870 \u2013 July 12, 1938) was a [[Mexican Americans|Mexican-American]] botanist known for her collection of novel plant specimens from areas of [[Mexico]], [[Peru]], and [[Colombia]]. She discovered a new genus of ''[[Asteraceae]]'' and was the most accomplished plant collector of her time. Botanist and explorer Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda, braved earthquakes, bogs, and poisonous berries all for the sake of botanical discoveries.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://canadajournal.net/world/ynes-mexia-google-doodle-honors-tenacious-mexican-american-and-explorer-59595-2019/|title=Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda: Google Doodle Honors tenacious Mexican-American and explorer|last=News|date=2019-09-15|website=Canada Journal - News of the World|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nYn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda was born in 1870 in Washington, D.C. to Enrique Mex\u00eda and Sarah Wilmer Mex\u00eda.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf|title=Research Archive Cal Academy|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She was the daughter of a Mexican diplomat and the granddaughter of a Mexican general. When she was very young, her parents divorced. Her father returned to Mexico, and her mother moved the family to Texas. Mex\u00eda later moved to Mexico.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nybg.org/blogs/science-talk/2015/02/late-bloomer-the-short-prolific-career-of-ynes-mexia/|title=Late Bloomer: The Short, Prolific Career of Ynes Mexia|date=2015-02-26|website=Science Talk Archive|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> \n\n{{Citation needed span|text=In 1909, in her late thirties, she suffered a mental and physical breakdown that spurred her to move to San Francisco and seek medical care.|date=March 2020|reason=}} Her second husband continued to live in Mexico, and they eventually separated. There she started going on excursions into the mountains of Northern California with the [[Sierra Club]] and fell in love with the redwoods, the birds, the plants, and the quiet. <ref name=\":4\" /> She became involved in social work and was an active member of the [[Sierra Club]], which motivated her to attend the University of California, Berkeley.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nHer interest in botanical collecting began in 1922 when she joined an expedition led by [[Eustace L. Furlong|Eustace. L. Furlong]], a Berkeley paleontologist. She then enrolled in a course on flowering plants at the [[Hopkins Marine Station]] with [[LeRoy Abrams]] in Pacific Grove, California.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucjepsarchives.berkeley.edu/archon/?p=collections/findingaid&id=77&q=&rootcontentid=7350|title=Ynes Mexia collection, 1918-1966 {{!}} University and Jepson Herbaria Archives, University of California, Berkeley|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> A 1980 letter from [[John Thomas Howell]] reminisces about the autumn of 1923:<blockquote>\"When I was enrolled in freshman botany at UCB and Mrs. Mex\u00eda was attending advanced classes... We were on a field trip with the Calypso Club, the student botanical club. We had spent the day under the guidance of Herbert Mason (then a graduate student under Prof. Jepson) exploring the floristic riches of Jasper Ridge... Separated from the rest of the club, we made a wrong turn...reached the station long after our train had departed... Eventually we arrived in Berkeley (by train to San Francisco, streetcar to Ferry Building, ferry across the Bay, interurban to Berkeley, streetcar to our homes). Mrs. Mex\u00eda never let me forget it!\" </blockquote>At that time, it was very remarkable for that experience to have occurred unchaperoned.<ref name=\":6\" /> In 1924 she became a United States citizen.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://latinonaturalhistory.biodiversityexhibition.com/en/card/ynes-mexia|title=Ynes Mexia {{!}} Latino Natural History|website=latinonaturalhistory.biodiversityexhibition.com|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> \n\nIn July of 1925, at the age of 55, Yn\u00e9s wrote to [[Alice Eastwood]], letting Eastwood know that she was about to accompany Stanford's Assistant Herbarium Curator, [[Roxana Stinchfield Ferris|Roxanna Ferris]], on a collecting trip to Mexico. This would be her first botanical exploration trip to Mexico. Once in Mexico, Mex\u00eda decided that she could accomplish more on her own and abandoned the group, traveling the country for two years and collecting more than 1,500 specimens.<ref name=\":5\" /> The trip resulted in 500 species being collected, including one named in Mex\u00eda's honor, ''Mimosa mexiae''. Finally, in middle age, Mex\u00eda had found her purpose in life, writing: \"\u2026 I have a job, [where] I produce something real and lasting.\"<ref name=\":7\" /> She made three additional expeditions to Mexico and collected throughout South America in remote areas of [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]], [[Ecuador]], and [[Peru]]. She also collected in [[Alaska]] and other areas of the continental United States.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nAfter her first major expedition to [[Sinaloa|Sinaloa, Mexico]] in 1925, she spent 13 years traveling from Alaska to [[Tierra del Fuego]], often shocking those she met because she was traveling solo, riding horseback with knickers, and preferring to sleep outside even when a bed was available. \"A well-known collector and explorer stated very positively that 'it was impossible for a woman to travel alone in Latin America,'\" she wrote, continuing, \"I decided that if I wanted to become better acquainted with the South American continent the best way would be to make my way right across it.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1938, during an expedition to [[Oaxaca]], Mexico, Mex\u00eda became ill. She tried to continue but had to turn back and return to the United States, where she was diagnosed with lung cancer. She died within one month at age 68. [[William Edward Colby|William E. Colby]], the secretary of the Sierra Club, wrote, \"All who knew Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda could not fail to be impressed by her friendly unassuming spirit, and by that rare courage which enabled her to travel, much of the time alone, in lands where few would dare to follow.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outsideonline.com/2390204/ynes-mexia-plant-collector|title=This Trailblazing Plant Collector Found Solace in Nature|last=Siber|first=Kate|date=2019-02-20|website=Outside Online|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn the same 1980 letter where he described his student botanical club adventure with Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda, [[John Thomas Howell]] refers to her as a \"close friend of Alice Eastwood.\" He continues, \"In 1933 she accompanied Miss Eastwood and me on the first Eastwood and Howell collecting expedition.\u2026.in an open Model T Ford, that traversed parts of Nevada, Utah, Arizona, and California...and netted over 1300 collection numbers... Mrs. Mex\u00eda was to me a dear good friend.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Career ==\nOnce, Mex\u00eda joined a collecting trip to Mexico where she fell off a cliff, injuring her hand and fracturing her ribs.<ref name=\":7\" /> No obstacle could stand in Mex\u00eda's way, whether that be broken bones, poison, or dangerous terrain. She was an adventurer in the name of science. In 1928 she was hired to collect plants in Alaska. The next year she went to South America and travelled by canoe down the Amazon River, covering 4,800 kilometres in two and a half years to its source in the Andes.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000033443|title=Mexia, Ynes Enriquetta Julietta (1870-1938) on JSTOR|website=plants.jstor.org|doi=10.1093/anb/9780198606697.article.1302002|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> Her specimens were widely distributed to herbaria throughout the United States and western Europe. In addition to collecting, Mex\u00eda wrote articles and gave lectures describing her adventures and travels.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nDuring her collecting trips, Mex\u00eda would occasionally join other expeditions, including one headed by [[A. S. Hitchcock|A.S. Hitchcock]] and [[Mary Agnes Chase|Agnes Chase]] of the [[United States National Herbarium|U.S. National Herbarium]], and [[Thomas Harper Goodspeed|T. Harper Goodspeed]]'s University of California Botanical Expedition. Mex\u00eda learned how to collect from Alice Eastwood of the [[California Academy of Sciences]]. [[Nina Floy Bracelin]] served as Mex\u00eda's collection manager, caring for the specimens and sending them out for identification.<ref name=\":7\" /> Credit is due to Bracelin, affectionately known as \"Bracie,\" who prepared Mex\u00eda's specimens for herbaria. She worked diligently to label the specimens, sending sets to specialists so their species could be determined and distributing the duplicates. Mex\u00eda was said to be more interested in exploration and discovery rather than preparing her specimens, but her legacy lives on through those preserved botanical collections.<ref name=\":5\" /> In her will, Mex\u00eda left enough money to the California Academy of Sciences to hire Bracelin as an assistant to Alice Eastwood.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nMex\u00eda was an active member of many scientific societies, including the [[California Botanical Society]], the [[Sierra Club]], the Audubon Association of the Pacific, the Sociedad Geogr\u00e1fica de Lima, and the California Academy of Sciences. She was also an honorary member of the Departamento Forestal, de Caza y Pesca de Mexico. Her specimens can be viewed at the California Academy of Sciences (main collection), the [[Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia]], the [[Field Museum of Natural History]], the [[Harvard University Herbaria|Gray Herbarium]], the [[New York Botanical Garden]], the [[United States National Herbarium|Smithsonian Institution]], the [[University of California, Berkeley]], and the [[United States National Arboretum|U.S. National Arboretum]], as well as several museums and botanical gardens throughout Europe. Her personal papers are preserved at the California Academy of Sciences and at the [[Bancroft Library]] at the University of California, Berkeley.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Accomplishments ==\nMex\u00eda was also unusual for an American botanical collector during that era. Not only was she a woman, she was also of Mexican heritage and suffered some prejudice in a largely white field, and she was older\u2014she started her career in her mid-fifties. \"Women were actively dissuaded from doing that kind of work, because it was considered unfeminine and dangerous,\" says Vassiliki Betty Smocovitis, a professor of the history of biological sciences at the University of Florida. \"You actually have to camp out, you couldn\u2019t wash your hair, you were living a kind of rough life, and that could be dangerous\u2026. But Mex\u00eda had agency. She was doing exactly the work that she wanted to do.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Mex\u00eda had a life membership in the California Academy of Sciences and published a book, ''Brazilian Ferns Collected by Yn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda'', with [[Edwin Copeland|Edwin Bingham Copeland]], in 1932.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Brazillian Ferns Collected by Ynes Mexia|last=Mexia|first=Ynes|publisher=The University of California Press|year=1932|isbn=|location=Berkeley|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThough Mex\u00eda had a short professional career\u2014only 13 years\u2014compared to many other academics, she collected a huge number of plant specimens. According to the British Natural History museum, she collected at least 145,000 plant specimens during her travels,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://plants.jstor.org/stable/10.5555/al.ap.person.bm000033443|title=Mexia, Ynes Enriquetta Julietta (1870-1938) on JSTOR|last=|first=|date=|website=plants.jstor.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> 500 of which were new species.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://ucjepsarchives.berkeley.edu/archon/?p=collections/findingaid&id=77&q=&rootcontentid=7350|title=Ynes Mexia collection, 1918-1966|last=|first=|date=|website=University and Jepson Herbaria Archives, [[University of California, Berkeley]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> During her first expedition, she collected 500 specimens, which is the same number collected during Darwin's voyage on the Beagle.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://massivesci.com/articles/ynes-mexia-our-heroes/|title=Meet Ynes Mexia, late-blooming botanist whose adventures rivaled Darwin\u2019s|last=Serrato Marks|first=Gabriela|date=|website=massivesci.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref> Although curators are still working to catalogue her full selection of specimens, 50 new species have already been named after her.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n<br /> \n<references />{{Copyvio/core\n|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2014/8/2/1302842/-Women-in-Science-Ynes-Mexia-1870-1938 http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54\n|month = September\n|day = 16\n|year = 2019\n|time = 23:22\n|timestamp = 20190916232247}}\n<!-- Do not use the \"Copyvio/core\" template directly; the above line is generated by {{subst:Copyvio}} -->\nYn\u00e9s Mex\u00eda was born in [[Washington, D.C.]] on May 24, 1870, to her Mexican diplomat father, [[Enrique Mex\u00eda]] (son of Mexican general [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Mex\u00eda]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-04-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921191022/https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54 |archive-date=2018-09-21 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>), and Sarah Wilmer. The marriage broke up in 1873, when Yn\u00e9s was three years old, and her father went back to Mexico City. Her mother took the children, including Yn\u00e9s and six others from a previous marriage,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2014/8/2/1302842/-Women-in-Science-Ynes-Mexia-1870-1938|title=Women in Science: Ynes Mexia 1870\u20131938|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> and moved the area of present-day [[Mexia, Texas]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf|title=Ynes Mexia (1870\u20131938) Biographical Sketch by Jane Radcliffe, Archives Volunteer|last=Radcliffe|first=Jane|date=June 23, 2011|website=Ynes Mexia (1870\u20131938) Biographical Sketch by Jane Radcliffe, Archives Volunteer|publisher=California Academy of Sciences|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54|title=Mexia de Reygades, Ynes|last=Garc\u00eda|first=Mar\u00eda-Cristina Garc\u00eda|date=June 15, 2010|website=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMex\u00eda spent most of her childhood in Texas and received her secondary education in private schools in Philadelphia and Ontario, Canada.<ref name=\":2\" /> She attended Saint Joseph's Academy in [[Emmitsburg, Maryland]]; after she finished there, she moved to [[Mexico City]], where she lived at the family [[hacienda]] for 10 years and took care of her father, who died in 1896.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|McLoone|1997|pp=23\u201330}} She planned to become a nun, but her father's will stipulated that if she did, she would be cut out of the inheritance she shared with a stepsister. She and her stepsister fought over the money with her father's mistress and a stepbrother.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe married Herman de Laue, a Spanish-German merchant, in 1897, but the brief marriage ended upon his death in 1904.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}} Her second marriage, to D. Augustin Reygados, 16 years her junior, was also short-lived. He badly mismanaged her poultry business while she received medical treatment in San Francisco, leading her to divorce him in 1908.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}<ref name=\":0\" /> After her marriage to Reygados ended, she began a career as a [[social worker]] in [[San Francisco]]. In 1921, she matriculated at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], motivated by trips with the [[Sierra Club]], where a [[botany]] class sparked her interest in the field; however, she never received a degree.{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Bailey|1994|pp=248\u201349}} She died in Berkeley on July 12, 1938, from [[lung cancer]] after falling ill on a collecting trip to Mexico.{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Career and legacy==\n<!-- Please do not remove or change this Copyvio message until the issue is settled -->\n{{Nobots}}\n{{Copyvio/core\n|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2014/8/2/1302842/-Women-in-Science-Ynes-Mexia-1870-1938 http://researcharchive.calacademy.org/research/library/special/bios/Mexia.pdf https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fme54\n|month = September\n|day = 16\n|year = 2019\n|time = 23:23\n|timestamp = 20190916232311}}\n<!-- Do not use the \"Copyvio/core\" template directly; the above line is generated by {{subst:Copyvio}} -->\nMex\u00eda began her botany career at the age of 55 with a 1925 trip to western [[Mexico]] under the tutelage of [[Roxana Stinchfield Ferris|Roxanna Ferris]], a botanist at [[Stanford University]]. Mex\u00eda fell off a cliff and was injured, halting the trip, which yielded 500 specimens, including several new species. The first species to be named after her, ''[[Mimosa mexiae]]'', was discovered on this excursion.{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}}\n\nOver the next 13 years, she traveled to [[Argentina]], [[Chile]], [[Denali]] (in 1928), [[Brazil]] (in 1929), [[Ecuador]] (in 1934), [[Peru]] and the Straits of Magellan (in 1935), and southwestern Mexico (in 1937) on seven different collecting trips, discovering one new genus, ''[[Mexianthus]]'', and many new species among her 150,000 total specimens.{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}}{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}}{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}} She frequently traveled alone, which was rare for women in the early 20th century.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://massivesci.com/articles/ynes-mexia-our-heroes/|title=Meet Ynes Mexia, late-blooming botanist whose adventures rivaled Darwin\u2019s|last=Serrato Marks|first=Gabriela|date=2019-05-03|website=[[Massive Science]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref> During her trip to Western Mexico, she collected over 33,000 specimens,{{sfn|Ogilvie|Harvey|2000|pp=889\u201390}} including 50 new species.{{sfn|Oakes|2002|pp=252\u201353}} In Ecuador, Mex\u00eda worked with the Bureau of Plant Industry and Exploration, part of Ecuador's Department of Agriculture.{{sfn|Mongillo|2001|pp=179\u201380}} There, she looked for the wax palm, [[cinchona]], and herbs that bind to the soil.{{sfn|Mongillo|2001|pp=179\u201380}} Mex\u00eda once traveled up the [[Amazon River]] to its source in the Andes mountains with a guide and three other men in a canoe.{{sfn|McLoone|1997|pp=23\u201330}} She also spent three months living with the [[Aguaruna people| Araguarunas]],{{efn-ua|\"Aguaruna\" and \"Araguaruna\" seem to be used interchangeably in the botanical and ethnographic literatures. E.g., from the bibliography of [https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2FBF02864549 Folk taxonomy and evolutionary dynamics of cassava: A case study in Ubatuba, Brazil] (underlining added):\n* BOSTER, J.S. Classification, cultivation, and selection of {{uu|Araguaruna}} cultivars of ''Manihot esculenta'' (Euphorbiaceae). '''Advances in Economic Botany''', v.1, p.34-47, 1984.\n* BOSTER, J.S. Selection for perceptual distinctiveness: evidence from {{uu|Aguaruna}} cultivars of ''Manihot esculenta''. '''Economic Botany''', v.39, n.3, p.310-325, 1985.}} \na native group in the Amazon.{{sfn|McLoone|1997|pp=23\u201330}} All of these excursions were funded by the sale of her specimens to collectors and institutions alike.{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}} Specimens from these trips were stored in the [[Gray Herbarium]] at [[Harvard University]] and the [[Field Museum of Natural History]] in [[Chicago]].{{sfn|Bailey|1994|pp=248\u201349}}\n\nShe often lectured in the San Francisco [[San Francisco Bay Area|Bay Area]], sharing stories and photographs of her travels.<ref name=\":2\" /> Notes on her expeditions appeared regularly in ''The Gull'', the newsletter of the Audubon Society of the Pacific, between 1926 and 1935.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The ''[http://vault.sierraclub.org/history/bulletin/ Sierra Club Bulletin]'' published two accounts of her adventures, \"Three Thousand Miles up the Amazon\" (SCB, 18:1 [1933], 88\u201396),<ref name=\"vault.sierraclub.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://vault.sierraclub.org/history/bulletin/#M|title=Sierra Club Bulletin  \u2013 History |publisher= Sierra Club|website=vault.sierraclub.org|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> and \"Camping on the Equator\" (SCB, 22:1 [1937], 85\u201391).<ref name=\"vault.sierraclub.org\"/> Several accounts of her expeditions were published in ''[http://calbotsoc.org/madrono/ Madrono]'', the journal of the [[California Botanical Society]]. It also published a biographical note after her death in 1938 (''Madrono'', October, 1938, Vol. IV, No. 8, 274\u201375).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://calbotsoc.org/80-year-index/|title=California Botanical Society|last=Society|first=California Botanical|website=calbotsoc.org|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref> She was a member of the [[California Botanical Society]], the [[Sierra Club]], the Audubon Association of the Pacific, the [http://www.socgeolima.org.pe/ Sociedad Geografica de Lima, Peru], and had been made a life member of the [[California Academy of Sciences]]. She was also an honorary member of the Departamento Forestal y de Casa y Pesca de Mexico.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMex\u00eda was remembered by her colleagues for her expertise on life in the field and her resilience in the tough conditions,{{sfn|Yount|1999|pp=150\u201351}} as well as her impulsiveness and fractious but generous personality.{{sfn|Bailey|1994|pp=248\u201349}} They lauded her meticulous, careful work and her skills as a collector.{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}\n\nThere is substantial agreement that Mex\u00eda collected some 150,000 specimens in her lifetime.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Women in the Field: America's Pioneer Naturalists.|last=Bonta|first=Marcia Myers|authorlink=Marcia Bonta|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|year=1991|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Estimates of new species range from two to 500.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [http://vault.sierraclub.org/history/bulletin/ Sierra Club Bulletin] credits her with two new genera.<ref name=\":1\" /> ''[[Mexianthus]]'', named for Mex\u00eda, is a genus of [[Asteraceae]].{{sfn|Petrusso|1999|pp=391\u201392}}\n\nHer specimen collections can be viewed at the California Academy of Sciences.<ref name=\":1\" /> Portions are duplicated at the [[Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University|Academy of Natural Sciences]], Philadelphia; [[Catholic University of America|Catholic University, Washington, D.C.]]; [[Field Museum of Natural History|the Field Museum of Natural History, Chicago]]; [[Harvard University Herbaria|Gray Herbarium]], Harvard University; the [[University of California, Berkeley|University of California]], Berkeley; and important museums and botanical gardens in London, Copenhagen, Geneva, Paris, Stockholm, and Zurich. Her personal papers are at the California Academy of Sciences and at the [[Bancroft Library]] at UC Berkeley.\n\n===Google Doodle===\n\nMex\u00eda's legacy was recognized in the [[Google Doodle]] for September 15, 2019.\n<br />\n{{Botanist|Mexia}}\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of women in science]]\n* [[List of botanists|Botanists]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Notelist-ua}}\n;Citations\n{{reflist}}\n\n;References\n* {{citation\n  | title = American Women in Science\n  | last = Bailey\n  | first = Martha J.\n  | year = 1994\n  | publisher = ABC-CLIO\