[Slayer]] \u2013 ''[[Divine Intervention (album)|Divine Intervention]]''\n* [[Sodom (band)|Sodom]] \u2013 ''[[Get What You Deserve]]''\n* [[Solitude Aeturnus]] \u2013 ''[[Through the Darkest Hour]]''\n* [[Solstice (British band)|Solstice]] \u2013 ''[[Lamentations (album)|Lamentations]]''\n* [[Soundgarden]] \u2013 ''[[Superunknown]]''\n* [[Stabbing Westward]] \u2013 ''[[Ungod]]''\n* [[Stone Temple Pilots]] \u2013 ''[[Purple (Stone Temple Pilots album)|Purple]]''\n* [[Stratovarius]] \u2013 ''[[Dreamspace]]''\n* [[Suicidal Tendencies]] \u2013 ''[[Suicidal for Life]]''\n* [[Symphony X]] \u2013 ''[[Symphony X (album)|Symphony X]]''\n* [[Tankard (band)|Tankard]] \u2013 ''[[Two-Faced (Tankard album)|Two-Faced]]''\n* [[Testament (band)|Testament]] \u2013 ''[[Low (Testament album)|Low]]''\n* [[Therapy?]] \u2013 ''[[Troublegum]]''\n* [[Threshold (band)|Threshold]] \u2013 ''[[Psychedelicatessen (Threshold album)|Psychedelicatessen]]''\n* [[The 3rd and the Mortal]] \u2013 ''[[Sorrow (album)|Sorrow]]'' (EP)\n* The 3rd and the Mortal \u2013 ''[[Tears Laid in Earth]]''\n* [[Tiamat (band)|Tiamat]] \u2013 ''[[Wildhoney]]''\n* [[Urban Dance Squad]] \u2013 ''[[Persona Non Grata (album)|Persona Non Grata]]''\n* [[Vader (band)|Vader]] \u2013 ''[[Sothis (EP)|Sothis]]'' (EP)\n* [[Vanden Plas (band)|Vanden Plas]] \u2013 ''[[Colour Temple]]''\n* Various Artists \u2013 ''[[Nativity in Black]]'' ([[Black Sabbath]] tribute album)\n* [[Vicious Rumors]] \u2013 ''[[Word of Mouth (Vicious Rumors album)|Word of Mouth]]''\n* [[Widowmaker (Dee Snider band)|Widowmaker]] \u2013 ''Stand by for Pain''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Disbandments==\n*[[Atheist (band)|Atheist]] (reformed in [[2006 in heavy metal music|2006]])\n*[[Follow for Now]] \n*[[Lost Horizon (band)|Lost Horizon (then known as Highlander)]] (reformed in [[1999 in heavy metal music|1999]])\n*[[Metal Church]] (reformed in [[1998 in heavy metal music|1998]])\n*[[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n\n==Events==\n* [[Korn]] release their critically acclaimed self-titled debut album, which is generally considered the first ever \"[[nu metal]]\" album.\n* ''[[Divine Intervention (album)|Divine Intervention]]'' by [[Slayer]] peaks at Number 8 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with 93,000 copies sold in its first week, and later that year was certified gold in Canada and United States.\n* [[Nicholas Barker]] becomes the drummer for [[Cradle of Filth]].\n* Longtime [[Extreme (band)|Extreme]] drummer [[Paul Geary]] leaves the band is replaced by [[Mike Mangini|Michael Mangini]].\n* [[Testament (band)|Testament]] release their sixth album ''[[Low (Testament album)|Low]]''. It is their first album recorded without original guitarist [[Alex Skolnick]] and drummer [[Louie Clemente]], who both left the band [[1993 in heavy metal music|a year before]], and also their last with longtime bassist [[Greg Christian]], who left [[1996 in heavy metal music|two years later]].\n* [[Metallica]], [[Danzig (band)|Danzig]] and [[Suicidal Tendencies]] embark on a U.S. tour together.\n* [[Oomph!]] establish the [[Neue Deutsche H\u00e4rte]] genre with their album ''[[Sperm (album)|Sperm]]''.\n* Vocalist [[Ralf Scheepers]] leaves [[Gamma Ray (band)|Gamma Ray]]. He would later go on to form [[Primal Fear (band)|Primal Fear]].\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Timeline box|title=[[Timeline of heavy metal music|Heavy Metal Timeline]]|before=[[1993 in heavy metal music|1993]]|after=[[1995 in heavy metal music|1995]]|year=1994}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Timeline of heavy metal and hard rock music}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1994 In Heavy Metal Music}}\n[[Category:1990s in heavy metal music]]\n[[Category:1994 in music|Metal]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLamentations (disambiguation)(link changed toLamentations (Solstice album)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1994_in_heavy_metal_music"}
{"title_page": "Gian Pyres", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Gian Pyres\n| image                 =\n| caption            =\n| image_size            =\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Gianpiero Piras\n| alias               = Gian Piras\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1973|10|20}}\n| death_date                =\n| origin              = [[London]], [[England]]\n| instrument          = [[Guitar]]\n| genre               = [[Death metal]], [[black metal]], [[gothic metal]], [[doom metal]]\n| occupation          =\n| years_active        =\n| label               =\n| associated_acts     = [[The Rotted]]<br>[[Cradle of Filth]]<br>[[Dragonlord (band)|Dragonlord]]<br>Screamin' Daemon<br>[[Christian Death]]<br>[[Extreme Noise Terror]]<br>[[Solstice (UK doom metal band)|Solstice]]<br>[[Bal-Sagoth]]<br>[[Ship of Fools]]\n| website                 = http://www.myspace.com/gian_pyres\n}}\n\n'''Gian Pyres''' (born '''Gianpiero Piras''', 20 October 1973) is a [[British people|British]] [[guitarist]], best known for his work with [[extreme metal]] band [[Cradle of Filth]]<ref name=\"cof\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p200252|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography-Cradle of Filth|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref> for which he recorded guitars for ''[[Cruelty and the Beast]]'' (1998), ''[[Midian]]'' (2000), ''[[Bitter Suites to Succubi]]'' (2001) and ''[[Lovecraft & Witch Hearts]]'' (2002). He appeared on their [[DVD]]s ''[[Heavy, Left-Handed and Candid]]'' (2001), ''[[Live Bait for the Dead]]'' (2001) and ''[[Peace Through Superior Firepower]]'' (2005), and appeared in [[Alex Chandon]]'s ''[[Cradle of Fear]]'' (2001). In addition he has appeared in music videos for ''[[From the Cradle to Enslave]]'' (1999), ''[[Her Ghost in the Fog]]'' (2000), ''Born in a Burial Gown'' (2001) and ''Scorched Earth Erotica'' (2002). He also appeared with [[Cradle of Filth]] on [[BBC]]'s ''Living with the Enemy'' (1998).\n\nOther live and recording appearances include [[Ship of Fools]], [[Solstice (UK doom metal band)|Solstice]] ''[[Lamentations (Solstice album)|Lamentations]]'' EP (1994) and ''Halcyon'' (1995), and [[Dragonlord (band)|Dragonlord]] as touring guitarist (2005-6). He also recorded as a guest guitarist for [[Bal-Sagoth]] on ''[[A Black Moon Broods over Lemuria]]'' (1995), [[Christian Death]] on ''Born Again Anti-Christian'' (2000),<ref name=\"cred\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p467418|pure_url=yes}}|title=Credits-Gian Pyres|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref> [[Extreme Noise Terror]] on ''[[Being and Nothing]]'' (2001)<ref name=\"cred\" /> and [[Italy|Italian]] symphonic black metal band [[Theatres des Vampires]] on ''[[Vampyr\u00ecsme...]]'' (2003). He played for [[The Rotted]] (formerly known as [[Gorerotted]]) until November 2009, co-wrote and recorded ''Get Dead Or Die Trying'' (2008) and featured on the video ''Nothing But a Nosebleed''. He is currently a member of Screamin' Daemon, appearing on the yet unreleased album ''Wrath of the Genocide Gods''; and is the touring guitarist with former [[Cradle of Filth]] bandmate Sarah Jezebel Deva's solo band.\n\nHe is endorsed by [[PRS Guitars]] and [[Peavey Electronics|Peavey]].\n\nGian Piras has also worked for game developer [[The Creative Assembly]]/[[SEGA]], in Sussex, England on ''[[Rome: Total War]]'', ''[[Rome Total War: Barbarian Invasion]]'' and ''[[Medieval 2: Total War]]''. He also represented The Creative Assembly as a games technician on [[BBC2]]'s ''[[Time Commanders]]''. He currently resides in Canada with his Wife.\n\n==Equipment==\n*[[PRS Guitars]] \u2013 Private Stock Custom Pyres Edition\n*[[Gibson Guitars]] \u2013 Standard [[Gibson SG|SG]]\n*[[Peavey Electronics|Peavey]] Amps \u2013 6505\n*[[Peavey Electronics|Peavey]] or [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] cabinets\n*Effects by [[Boss Corporation|BOSS]] and [[Line 6 (company)|Line 6]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.myspace.com/gian_pyres Gian Pyres at Myspace]\n{{Cradle of Filth}}\n{{Theatres des Vampires}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pyres, Gian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Cradle of Filth members]]\n[[Category:Black metal musicians]]\n[[Category:British people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Gian Pyres\n| image                 =\n| caption            =\n| image_size            =\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Gianpiero Piras\n| alias               = Gian Piras\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1973|10|20}}\n| death_date                =\n| origin              = [[London]], [[England]]\n| instrument          = [[Guitar]]\n| genre               = [[Death metal]], [[black metal]], [[gothic metal]], [[doom metal]]\n| occupation          =\n| years_active        =\n| label               =\n| associated_acts     = [[The Rotted]]<br>[[Cradle of Filth]]<br>[[Dragonlord (band)|Dragonlord]]<br>Screamin' Daemon<br>[[Christian Death]]<br>[[Extreme Noise Terror]]<br>[[Solstice (UK doom metal band)|Solstice]]<br>[[Bal-Sagoth]]<br>[[Ship of Fools]]\n| website                 = http://www.myspace.com/gian_pyres\n}}\n\n'''Gian Pyres''' (born '''Gianpiero Piras''', 20 October 1973) is a [[British people|British]] [[guitarist]], best known for his work with [[extreme metal]] band [[Cradle of Filth]]<ref name=\"cof\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p200252|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography-Cradle of Filth|last=Ankeny|first=Jason|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref> for which he recorded guitars for ''[[Cruelty and the Beast]]'' (1998), ''[[Midian]]'' (2000), ''[[Bitter Suites to Succubi]]'' (2001) and ''[[Lovecraft & Witch Hearts]]'' (2002). He appeared on their [[DVD]]s ''[[Heavy, Left-Handed and Candid]]'' (2001), ''[[Live Bait for the Dead]]'' (2001) and ''[[Peace Through Superior Firepower]]'' (2005), and appeared in [[Alex Chandon]]'s ''[[Cradle of Fear]]'' (2001). In addition he has appeared in music videos for ''[[From the Cradle to Enslave]]'' (1999), ''[[Her Ghost in the Fog]]'' (2000), ''Born in a Burial Gown'' (2001) and ''Scorched Earth Erotica'' (2002). He also appeared with [[Cradle of Filth]] on [[BBC]]'s ''Living with the Enemy'' (1998).\n\nOther live and recording appearances include [[Ship of Fools]], [[Solstice (UK doom metal band)|Solstice]] ''[[Lamentations (album)|Lamentations]]'' EP (1994) and ''Halcyon'' (1995), and [[Dragonlord (band)|Dragonlord]] as touring guitarist (2005-6). He also recorded as a guest guitarist for [[Bal-Sagoth]] on ''[[A Black Moon Broods over Lemuria]]'' (1995), [[Christian Death]] on ''Born Again Anti-Christian'' (2000),<ref name=\"cred\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p467418|pure_url=yes}}|title=Credits-Gian Pyres|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=21 February 2010}}</ref> [[Extreme Noise Terror]] on ''[[Being and Nothing]]'' (2001)<ref name=\"cred\" /> and [[Italy|Italian]] symphonic black metal band [[Theatres des Vampires]] on ''[[Vampyr\u00ecsme...]]'' (2003). He played for [[The Rotted]] (formerly known as [[Gorerotted]]) until November 2009, co-wrote and recorded ''Get Dead Or Die Trying'' (2008) and featured on the video ''Nothing But a Nosebleed''. He is currently a member of Screamin' Daemon, appearing on the yet unreleased album ''Wrath of the Genocide Gods''; and is the touring guitarist with former [[Cradle of Filth]] bandmate Sarah Jezebel Deva's solo band.\n\nHe is endorsed by [[PRS Guitars]] and [[Peavey Electronics|Peavey]].\n\nGian Piras has also worked for game developer [[The Creative Assembly]]/[[SEGA]], in Sussex, England on ''[[Rome: Total War]]'', ''[[Rome Total War: Barbarian Invasion]]'' and ''[[Medieval 2: Total War]]''. He also represented The Creative Assembly as a games technician on [[BBC2]]'s ''[[Time Commanders]]''. He currently resides in Canada with his Wife.\n\n==Equipment==\n*[[PRS Guitars]] \u2013 Private Stock Custom Pyres Edition\n*[[Gibson Guitars]] \u2013 Standard [[Gibson SG|SG]]\n*[[Peavey Electronics|Peavey]] Amps \u2013 6505\n*[[Peavey Electronics|Peavey]] or [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] cabinets\n*Effects by [[Boss Corporation|BOSS]] and [[Line 6 (company)|Line 6]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.myspace.com/gian_pyres Gian Pyres at Myspace]\n{{Cradle of Filth}}\n{{Theatres des Vampires}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pyres, Gian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Cradle of Filth members]]\n[[Category:Black metal musicians]]\n[[Category:British people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLamentations (disambiguation)(link changed toLamentations (Solstice album)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gian_Pyres"}
{"title_page": "New Horizon College of Engineering", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2009}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n| name = \n| image_name = NHEI-22-06-2017-1.png\n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| established = 2001\n| type = Private Engineering College\n| parent = New Horizon Educational Institution\n| chairman = Dr. Mohan Manghnani\n| principal = Dr. Manjunatha\n| academic_staff = 350+ Faculty\n| students = 5500+ Students from across India\n| address = New Horizon Knowledge Park, Ring Road, Bellandur Post, Near Marathahalli, Bangalore.\n| city = [[Bangalore]]\n| state = [[Karnataka]]\n| postalcode = 560103\n| country = [[India]]\n| language = English\n| affiliations = Autonomous College, Permanently Affiliated to VTU, Belagavi\n| website = {{URL|http://www.newhorizonindia.edu/nhengineering}}\n| logo = \n}}\n[[File:NHCE Campus.jpg|thumb|New Horizon College of Engineering]]\n[[File:NHCE Campus pic 2.jpg|alt=|thumb|NHCE Campus]]\n'''New Horizon College of Engineering (NHCE)''' is an '''Autonomous college''', Permanently Affiliated to [[Visvesvaraya Technological University|Visvesvaraya Technological University(VTU),]] Approved by the [[All India Council for Technical Education|All India Council for Technical Education(AICTE)]] & [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission(UGC)]]. It is Accredited by [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council|NAAC]] with '''<nowiki/>'A' grade''' & [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council|NBA]]. \n\nThe institute places highest priority on innovative programs of instructions that include both traditional class room theory and professional skills training. There is a strong impetus on overall personality development of the students with emphasis on soft skills.Students are supported through mentoring and counseling systems. The management offers scholarships to meritorious students. At NHCE, we understand and respect our role as educators and from the moment a student walk into the campus, he/she is well guided to know his/her strengths and choose an area of functional specialization.This enables students to concentrate their efforts and energies to gain the competitive edge. NHCE has an unique distinction of achieving 100% admissions in all its courses year after year.\n\n'''Mission:''' To emerge as an institute of eminence in the fields of engineering, technology and management in serving the industry and the nation by empowering students with a high degree of technical, managerial and practical competence.\n\n'''Vision:'''\n\n* To strengthen the theoretical, practical and ethical dimensions of the learning process by fostering a culture of research and innovation among faculty members and students. \n* To encourage long-term interaction between the academia and industry through the involvement of the industry in the design of the curriculum and its hands-on implementation.\n* To strengthen and mold students in professional, ethical, social and environmental dimensions by encouraging participation in co-curricular and extracurricular activities.\n\n== History  ==\nNew Horizon College of Engineering is part of the New Horizon Educational Institution which was established in 1970; the college was established in 2001.\n\n== Location ==\nIt is located in the heart of the IT capital of India, [[Bangalore]]. The college campus is situated in the IT corridor of Bangalore (near Marathahalli) surrounded by [[Multinational corporation|MNCs]] and IT giants such as [[Intel]], [[Accenture]], [[Capgemini]], ARM, Symphony, [[Wipro]], [[Nokia]], [[JPMorgan Chase|JP Morgan]] and [[Cisco Systems|Cisco]] to name a few. NHCE has a scenic and serene campus that provides an environment which is conducive for personal and intellectual growth. The infrastructure acts as a facilitator for the effective delivery of the curriculum. NHCE boasts of state-of-the-art facilities for the students. Students are given utmost encouragement in their areas of interest by providing hi-tech facilities backed by faculty support. \n\n== Department ==\n\nThe college has the following departments:\n*[[Automotive engineering|Automobile Engineering]]\n* Basic Sciences & Humanities\n\n*[[Civil engineering|Civil Engineering]]\n*[[Computer engineering|Computer Engineering]]\n*[[Computer Science and Engineering|Computer Science & Engineering]]\n*Computer Science & Engineering ([https://www.sas.com/en_in/insights/articles/big-data/artificial-intelligence-machine-learning-deep-learning-and-beyond.html Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning])\n*[[Electrical & Electronics Engineering]]\n*[[Electronic engineering|Electronics & Communication Engineering]]\n*[[Information science|Information Science & Engineering]]\n*[[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical Engineering]]\n*[[Master of Computer Applications]] (MCA)\n* [[Master of Business Administration]] (MBA)\n\n==Accolades==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n| type = \n| NIRF_E_2019=Ranked 4th among Top Private Engineering College in Bangalore\n}}New Horizon College of Engineering has several achievements and accolades to its credit.\n\n* \u00a0'''Accredited by [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council|NAAC]] with \u2018A\u2019 Grade.'''\n\n* '''All UG programs are accredited by the [[National Board of Accreditation]] (NBA).'''\n* '''Ranked 4th among the Top Private Engineering Colleges in Bangalore as per [[National Institutional Ranking Framework|NIRF]] Ranking 2019''', announced by the [[Ministry of Human Resource Development|Ministry of HRD]], Govt. of India.\n* Students from New Horizon College of Engineering Selected for the World Famous \u201c The International Summer Space School: Future Space Technologies and Experiments in Space\u201d at the [[Samara National Research University]], Samara, [[Russia]].\n* Honored with the distinguished '''\"EXCELLENCE IN PROVIDING PREFERRED ENVIRONMENT FOR CAMPUS PLACEMENTS\"''' award. The award was presented by Hon'ble Minister of State for Skill Development & Entrepreneurship, Govt. of India, Mr. [[Mahendra Nath Pandey]] during 13th [[ASSOCHAM]] Higher Education, Skill & Livelihood Conclave held on 25th & 26th February 2020 at New Delhi. \n* Honored with the distinguished '''\"MOST PREFERRED INSTITUTE FOR PROVIDING GLOBAL EXPOSURE\"''' award. The award was presented by Hon'ble Minister of State for Skill Development & Entrepreneurship, Govt. of India, Mr. [[Mahendra Nath Pandey]] during 13th [[ASSOCHAM]] Higher Education, Skill & Livelihood Conclave held on 25th & 26th February 2020 at New Delhi. \n* Honored with the distinguished '''\u201cEXCELLENCE IN PROMOTING INDUSTRY-ACADEMIA INTERFACE\"''' award. The award was presented by Hon\u2019ble Former President of India, Dr[[Pranab Mukherjee|. Pranab Mukherjee]] during the [[ASSOCHAM]] Higher Education Sumit on February 21, 2019.\n* Honored with the distinguished '''\u201cMOST PREFERRED INSTITUTE WITH GLOBAL EXPOSURE\u201d''' award. The award was presented by Hon\u2019ble Minister for Commerce and Industry and Civil Aviation, GOI, Mr. [[Suresh Prabhu]] during the [[ASSOCHAM]] Higher Education Summit on February 21, 2019.\n* Awarded with the most coveted and prestigious \u201cBest Accredited Student Branch Award\u201d from the [[Computer Society of India]] for the academic year 2018-2019. This award was presented for organizing the highest number of quality events and activities. \u00a0\n* First Institution to achieve the rare honor of having '''Filed 201 Patents in 3 Years in India and in the World!''' It is a historical achievement and a rare feat of an Engineering College! \u00a0 \n* Ranked No.1 in Karnataka, 6th in South India, and 12th in India among the \u201cBest Private Tech Schools\u201d. Source: Data Quest T-School Survey June 2018. \n* Bagged 5 [[Visvesvaraya Technological University|VTU]] Ranks for the academic year 2017-18 (last batch of VTU) during the 18th VTU Convocation.\n* Honored with the distinguished \"'''Best International Education Collaboration of the Year\"''' award. The award was presented by [[Satya Pal Singh (Uttar Pradesh politician)|Dr. Satyapal Singh]], Hon\u2019ble of State for Human Resource Development, GOI, Higher Education, During [[ASSOCHAM]] Higher Education Sumit on February 17, 2018.\n* Awarded as the '''\u201cBest Institution towards Industry Focus Education Delivery for Full Employability\u201d'''. The award was presented by [[Satya Pal Singh (Uttar Pradesh politician)|Dr. Satyapal Singh]], Hon\u2019ble Minister of State for Human Resource Development, GOI, Higher Education, during [[ASSOCHAM]] Higher Education Summit on February 17, 2018.\n* Awarded as the '''\u201cBest Engineering College in India-South\u201d'''. The award was presented by [[Satya Pal Singh (Uttar Pradesh politician)|Dr. Satyapal Singh]], Hon\u2019ble Minister of State for Human Resource Development, GOI, Higher Education, during [[ASSOCHAM]] Higher Education Summit on February 17, 2018.\n* Awarded for filling Highest Number of Patents during the 32nd Indian Engineering Congress on 21st December 2017.\n* New Horizon College of Engineering, Ranked No. 2 in Karnataka, 5th in South India, and 15th in india among the\"BEST PRIVATE TECH SCHOOLS\". Source: Dataquest T-school Survey June 2017. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|New Horizon College of Engineering}}\n* {{Official website|http://newhorizonindia.edu/nhengineering}}\n\n[[Category:Engineering colleges in Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2001]]\n__INDEX__\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2009}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox university\n| name = NEW HORIZON COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING\n| image_name = NHEI-22-06-2017-1.png\n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| established = 2001\n| type = Private Engineering College\n| pa